{"title_page": "RAF Andreas", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name                = RAF Andreas\n| ensign              = Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg\n| nativename          = \n| nativename-a        = \n| nativename-r        = \n| image               = RAF roundel.svg\n| caption             = \n| IATA                = \n| ICAO                = \n| type                = Military\n| owner               = [[Air Ministry]]\n| operator            = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| city-served         = \n| location            = [[Andreas, Isle of Man|Andreas]], [[Isle of Man]]\n| built               = {{Start date|1940}}\n| used                = 1941-{{End date|1946}}\n| elevation-m         = 34\n| elevation-f         = {{Convert|34|m|disp=output number only|0}}\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|54|22|15|N|004|25|25|W|region:IM_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map         = Isle of Man\n| pushpin_label       = RAF Andreas\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Isle of Man\n| r1-number           = 06/24\n| r1-length-m         = 1000\n| r1-length-f         = 3280\n| r1-surface          = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number           = 11/29\n| r2-length-m         = 1000\n| r2-length-f         = 3280\n| r2-surface          = Asphalt\n| r3-number           = 17/35\n| r3-length-m         = 1000\n| r3-length-f         = 3280\n| r3-surface          = Asphalt\n| stat-year           = \n| stat1-header        = \n| stat1-data          = \n| stat2-header        = \n| stat2-data          = \n| footnotes           = Operational dates.<ref name=\"CT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.controltowers.co.uk/A/Andreas_Isle_of_Man.htm |title=RAF Andreas |publisher=Control Towers|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Royal Air Force Station Andreas''' or more simply '''RAF Andreas''' is a former [[Royal Air Force]] [[Royal Air Force station|station]] in the [[Isle of Man]] which was operational between 1941 and 1946.  It was built in fields between [[Andreas, Isle of Man|Andreas]] and [[Bride, Isle of Man|Bride]]. As was common practice, the station was named after the parish in which it was situated.<ref name=\"CT\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Construction===\nWhen the [[Luftwaffe]], in October 1940, began to attack British cities under the cover of darkness, the North West of England with its industrial centres and ports came within easy reach of German aircraft operating from [[occupied France]].  The first fighter squadron had arrived on the [[Isle of Man]] at nearby [[RAF Jurby]] in November 1940, and came under the control of the newly formed [[No. 9 Group RAF]], [[RAF Fighter Command|Fighter Command]].  Group Control was positioned at [[RAF Barton Hall]], near [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], and its sectors covered [[Lancashire]], [[Cheshire]] and [[Shropshire]].  Andreas was to be a separate sector with responsibility for the Irish Sea and its surrounds.  The new wing of [[Ramsey Grammar School]] was commissioned as Control Centre for the sector and was hastily prepared before the arrival of the new fighters at Jurby.  The Control Centre was linked to [[Chain Home|the three radar stations at Dalby, Scarlett and Bride]].<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p51\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=51.}}</ref>\n\nThe siting of a fighter airfield in the location of Andreas had been chosen because of its central location with regard to [[Liverpool]], [[Belfast]] and [[Glasgow]], as it was in an excellent position to provide protection to the vital shipping arriving at these ports. Finally, with the relevant compensation payments agreed, work on the construction of RAF Andreas began in earnest by the end of June 1940. A total of {{convert|500|acre}} of farmland was earmarked, {{convert|200|acre}} coming from both Ballaghaue Farm and Braust Farm, and a small portion of land was acquired which stretched into the adjacent parish of Bride.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturevannin.im/video_story_411491.html |title=World War Two (02) Defending the Island |publisher=[[Culture Vannin]] |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n[[File:Andreas Church (reduced tower).jpeg|thumb|left|[[St Andrew's Church, Andreas, Isle of Man|St Andrew's Church, Andreas]]. The tower was reduced on the request of the [[Air Ministry]] as it was seen as a danger to operations from the base.]]\nBy the spring of 1941 the airfield, to be built to the full specification of an operational fighter station, was beginning to take shape.  The main NE/SW runway was {{convert|1100|yd}} long and {{convert|50|yd}} wide and was obviously meant to take larger aircraft than fighters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forgottenairfields.com/united-kingdom/man/andreas-s961.html |title=Abandoned, Forgotten & Little Known Airfields in Europe: Andreas |website=forgottenairfields.com |author=Ronald V. |date=7 November 2010 |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>  From the perimeter track there was access to the flight dispersals in which a total of 24 blast pens (or E pens) were built, half to provide protection for the fighters while larger ones were for twin-engined aircraft.  Considerable thought had also gone into the airfield's defences, with the whole area being surrounded by {{convert|5|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} roller concertina barbed wire, with gaps located at the main entrance and crash gates<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p52\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=52.}}</ref> and by a [[tarmacadam]]ed perimeter track over three miles in distance.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Ramsey Courier, Friday, September 14, 1945; Page: 3</ref>\n\nRAF Andreas was designed as a dispersed airfield with many components of the base encompassed into the village of Andreas. The consequence of this was such that the domestic side and living quarters were a considerable distance from the technical side. There was also a dance and entertainments hall in the village and a farm on the Station.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nDuring the summer of 1941 the first RAF personnel arrived at Andreas.  This mainly consisted of a flight of [[Royal Air Force Police]], whose first duties were guarding the stores of supplies kept in the completed hangars.  Others arriving at that time included MT drivers and soldiers of the [[Wiltshire Regiment]], under the command of Major G.K. Wait [[Military Cross|MC]], who arrived to man the airfield's defences, along with the first of many [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force|WAAF]]s whose duties were to staff the administration offices and operations rooms. The station officially opened in August 1941, the first commanding officer of RAF Andreas being [[Group Captain]] J. Marson.<ref name=\"Man Times 1945\">''Isle of Man Times''. 14 September 1945.</ref>\n\n==Fighter Command==\n\n===Fighter Station===\n[[File:A Spitfire MkVb undergoing gun calibration at RAF Andreas, Isle of Man.jpg|thumb|A Spitfire MkVb of 457 Squadron undergoing gun calibration at RAF Andreas.]]\n\n===457 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 457 Squadron RAAF}}\n[[File:457 Squadron badge.jpeg.jpg|100px|left|457 Squadron badge.jpeg]]\nBy October 1941, RAF Andreas was ready to receive the first of [[No. 457 Squadron RAAF]] (457 Sqn)<ref name=\"ABCT\"/> Spitfires from [[RAF Jurby]] as a prelude to working up to operational efficiency.<ref name=\"Halley1988p478\">{{Harvnb|Halley|1988|p=478.}}</ref> This work-up would take six months, however the transfer of 457 Sqn's ground crew and administrative staff brought welcome relief to the congestion at [[Jurby]].<ref name=\"discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D8405567 |publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]] |title=Squadron Number: 457 RAAF (Royal Australian Air Force) |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref> It was also during this work-up period, that the [[Air Ministry]] insisted that the height of Andreas church tower be reduced, as it was a hazard, and in line with the southern end of the main runway.<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p55\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=55.}}</ref> The church tower was originally {{convert|120|ft}} high, and the most striking feature of the Island's northern plain being visible throughout the parish.<ref name=st-andrew>{{cite web |url=http://www.achurchnearyou.com/andreas-st-andrew/ |title=St Andrew, Andreas |publisher=[[The Church of England]] |website=achurchnearyou.com |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nRAF Andreas had become fully operational in March 1942, but by now 457 Sqn was ready to move south to join [[No. 11 Group RAF]] (11 Grp) at [[RAF Redhill]] and to take part in air strikes over northern [[France]].\n\n===452 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 452 Squadron RAAF}}\n[[File:452 Squadron RAAF Badge.jpg|70px|left|RAF312Sq]]Following the departure of 457 Squadron, it was immediately replaced by [[No. 452 Squadron RAAF]] (452 Sqn),<ref name=\"CT\"/> which had been formed in April 1941 and whose most celebrated pilot was the maverick Irishman, [[Paddy Finucane]].\n[[File:Ground Crew and pilot with Spitfire at RAF Andreas.png|thumb|right|Ground Crew and pilot with Spitfire at RAF Andreas]]\nIn June 1942, 452 Sqn's tenure at Andreas came to and end when the squadron returned to Australia,<ref name=\"awm.gov.au\">{{cite web |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/unit/U59437/ |title=No. 452 Squadron |publisher=Australian War Memorial |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref> sailing on 21 June, arriving in Melbourne on 13 August and re-assembled at [[RAAF Base Richmond|RAAF Richmond]], as [[No. 452 Squadron RAAF]], on 6 September.<ref name=\"awm.gov.au\"/><ref>https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/U59437</ref>\n\n===93 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 93 Squadron RAF}}\n[[File:Badge of No. 93 Squadron RAF.jpg|100px|left|RAF312Sq]]The third fighter unit to occupy RAF Andreas was [[No. 93 Squadron RAF]] (93 Sqn)<ref name=\"ABCT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/andreas |title=Andreas |publisher=Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust|access-date=29 April 2012}}</ref> which had an entirely different background, previously having been involved in the development of night fighter tactics using [[Douglas A-20 Havoc|Havoc]]s equipped with radar and [[Turbinlite]] searchlights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/93squadron.cfm |title=93 Squadron |publisher=Royal Air Force |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n93 Sqn reformed at Andreas as an entirely new squadron equipped with [[Spitfire]] VB's as it worked up to operational efficiency.<ref name=\"CT\"/><ref name=\"Halley1988p166\">{{Harvnb|Halley|1988|p=166.}}</ref> Considerable time was spent over the air-to-ground firing range along the Ayres coastline at Smeale which had been constructed not long after the first fighters had arrived at [[RAF Jurby]].  When Andreas airfield was under construction, the coastline north of Smeale had been heavily mined as a precaution against an enemy landing.  After four months, 93 Sqn was ready to move on to more direct action, and orders were received which would see the squadron re-locate to [[Algiers]] ready for the North African landings as part of [[Operation Torch]].<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p57\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=57.}}</ref>\n[[File:Supermarine Walrus.jpg|thumb|Supermarine Walrus]]\n\n===275 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 275 Squadron RAF}}\n[[File:No 275 Squadron Badge.png|80px|left|RAF312Sq]]In November 1941 RAF Andreas received a detachment from [[No. 275 Squadron RAF|275 Squadron]] (275 Sqn) which served as [[No. 9 Group RAF|9 Group's]] [[Air Sea Rescue]] Unit and which covered the [[Irish Sea]]. The Squadron had its administrative headquarters at [[RAF Valley]], [[Anglesey]],<ref name=\"CT\"/> and the detachment's [[Supermarine Walrus|Walrus amphibian Mk.I's]] were often to be seen flying around the Island.<ref name=\"Halley1988p342\">{{Harvnb|Halley|1988|p=342.}}</ref>\n\n===772 Squadron (FAA)===\n{{main|772 Naval Air Squadron}}\nAnother strange but permanent resident at Andreas, was a [[Vought-Sikorsky Chesapeake]] of the [[Fleet Air Arm]]. It belonged to [[772 Naval Air Squadron|772 Squadron]], [[Fleet Air Arm]] (772 Sqn),<ref name=\"ABCT\"/> and was employed to provide simulated conditions for the [[Royal Navy]]'s [[HMS Valkyrie (shore establishment)|No 1 Radar Training School]] which was situated on [[Douglas Head]]. The Chesapeake was replaced in October 1944, after crashing on Douglas Head, killing the pilot Sub Lieutenant R. S. Paton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manxgliding.org/features/andreasairfield/ |title=The History of Andreas Airfield  |publisher=Andreas Gliding Club |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n[[File:E pen RAF Andreas.jpg|thumb|An E-pen at RAF Andreas (2018). These were situated predominately on the eastern and northern side of the airfield and were designed to afford shelter from attack for aircraft and ground crew. Two aircraft could be accommodated within the pen. Today, this one houses a mobile phone mast.]]\n\n==Operations==\nAt night the drone of [[bomber]]s could be heard as they passed overhead on their way to Belfast. These were the nights when the fighters based at RAF Andreas and RAF Jurby were called into action.\n[[Radar in World War II|Airborne radar]] was still in its infancy, and there was little they could do except offer token resistance.\nOccasionally, and enemy aircraft would be sighted and in the ensuing chase bombs would be jettisoned as the [[Heinkel He 111|Heinkel]] or [[Dornier Do 17|Dornier]] made a rapid escape.\nThe [[air raid siren]]s of the Island sounded a total of 43 alerts&nbsp;\u2013 32 of them in 1942. Many were of a short duration, but on the nights of 20 and 21 December 1941, there were two alerts each lasting five hours when Liverpool and Manchester were being heavily attacked.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://liverpoolremembrance.weebly.com/christmas-blitz.html |title=Liverpool And Merseyside Remembered: Christmas Blitz |website=liverpoolremembrance.weebly.com |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/history/the-blitz-around-britain |title=The Blitz Around Britain |publisher=Imperial War Museums |first=Amanda |last=Mason |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe first enemy bomb to fall on the Isle of Man was on 18 September 1940, when [[high explosive]] bombs caused four large craters in the [[Dalby, Isle of Man|Dalby]] area&nbsp;\u2013 without damage or injury.<ref name=\"culturevannin.im\">{{cite web |url=http://www.culturevannin.im/video_story_411547.html |title=World War Two (09) Bombs in the Island |publisher=Culture Vannin |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\nOn the nights of 7, 15, and 16 April 1941, enemy bombers were again over the Island. On the first occasion the Island was illuminated with [[Flare (pyrotechnic)|flare]]s and [[incendiary bomb]]s landed near [[Port Soderick]].\nOn the 15th a high explosive bomb landed close to Cronk Ruagh [[Sanatorium]] near Ramsey. [[Shrapnel shell|Shrapnel]] landed on the entrance steps and windows were blown out.\nThe following night more H.E. bombs fell at [[Castletown, Isle of Man|Scarlett]] narrowly missing the [[Chain Home|Radar Station]].<ref name=\"culturevannin.im\"/>\n\nThe following month considerable alarm was caused when bombs fell on the outskirts of [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vimeo.com/129460328 |title=9. Bombing: The Second World War in the Isle of Man |publisher=Culture Vannin |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref> It was the night of 8/9 May, when clear conditions prevailed and when [[Bombing of Dublin in World War II|Dublin was mistakenly bombed]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/why-the-nazis-bombed-dublin-1075966.html |title=Why the Nazis bombed Dublin |last=Fisk |first=Robert |date=24 January 1999 |access-date=16 May 2017 |newspaper=The Independent16  }}</ref>\n\nAfter 93 Sqn had exchanged the sands of the Ayres for the sands of North Africa, the station grew quiet and much of it was reduced to care and maintenance. There was little to do for [[No. 9 Group RAF|9 Group]] now that the emergencies which had brought it into being had largely passed. Nevertheless, RAF Andreas remained officially part of 9 Group until August 1944, [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Raynor being responsible for the signing and despatch of the operational orders which signalled the disbanding of the Group, and many of the 900 airmen and 400 WAAFs were posted out whilst new plans were awaited for the Station.\n\nOne of the residents who did not leave was the detachment from [[No. 275 Squadron RAF|275 Squadron]] which would stay at the Station until the end of April, 1944.<ref name=\"CT\"/>\n\nDuring the spring of 1943, a new role was found for the excellent facilities at Andreas, and preparations began to set up '''No.11 Air Gunnery School of [[RAF Training Command|Training Command]]'''.<ref name=\"CT\"/>\n\n==Training Command==\n\n===No.11 Air Gunnery School===\nWith the specialisation required in aircrew for the heavy bombers of [[RAF Bomber Command|Bomber Command]], air gunners became a separate category. Each [[Avro Lancaster]] and [[Handley Page Halifax]] required two or three gunners in its crew, so thousands would be required to meet the demands of the growing strategic offensive and to replace losses.\n[[File:Miles Martinet.jpg|thumb|right|Martinet in RAF service]] [[File:Vickers Wellington - RAF Bomber Command HU108373.jpg|thumb|Vickers Wellington]]\nRAF Andreas was to play an important role in the training programme, and thus began the busiest period in the life of the station. The Station's new commanding officer was Group Captain Mackay, who would remain at Andreas for the rest of the war period, and the station completely changed in character from that of a fighter station to that of a training establishment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rafcommands.com/archive/09815.php |title=Air Gunnery Schools |publisher=Royal Air Force Commands |access-date=16 May 2017 |first=Tom |last=Williams |date=19 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\nWhilst at Andreas, the volunteer pupils selected for air gunners underwent an intensive ten-week course, before passing on to the operational training units of [[RAF Bomber Command]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~nbpennfi/penn8b1ADemandingTrainingRegime.htm |title=A Demanding Training Regime |website=rootsweb.ancestry.com |access-date=16 May 2017 |first=G. Christian |last=Larsen |publisher=Pennfield Parish Military Historical Society }}</ref> The course involved sighting; aircraft recognition; pyrotechnics; clay-pigeon and 25 yard range shoots; care and maintenance of .303 and .5 Browning machine guns and 20mm cannon; turret hydraulics, manipulation and operation, and the use of cine-camera guns. The training huts were equipped with the various types of turrets then in use, including [[Boulton Paul Aircraft|Boulton Paul]] Types A and F, and [[Frazer Nash]] 121 which were installed in the [[Handley Page Halifax]] and [[Avro Lancaster]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pilotfriend.com/photo_albums/timeline/ww2/Avro%20Lancaster.htm |title=Avro Lancaster |publisher=PilotFriend |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe first aircraft to arrive were 15 [[Avro Anson]] gunnery trainers. For more advanced experience, training was conducted on a succession of [[Vickers Wellington]]s which were being withdrawn from the front-line squadrons of Bomber Command, and target towing duties were the responsibility of [[Bristol Mercury]] engined [[Miles Martinet]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aviastar.org/air/england/miles_m-25.php |title=Miles M.25 Martinet  |access-date=16 May 2017 |website=aviastar.org \u2013 All the World's Rotorcraft }}</ref>\n\nFiring took place in allotted zones over the sea on both sides of the Point of Ayre, care being taken not to interfere with the Jurby bombing ranges.<ref name=\"Man Times 1945\"/>\n\nDespite the continual flying programme over the congested north of the Island, accidents involving Andreas aircraft proved to be very rare, and only one documented incident resulted in the loss of a life. During 1944, Andreas, because of the length of its main runway, became an emergency landing ground for the Atlantic ferry route and was occasionally used by American aircraft such as the [[B-17 Flying Fortress]] and the [[B-24 Liberator]].<ref name=\"Man Times 1945\"/> The ending of the war in [[Europe]] in May 1945, saw no let up in the routine at Andreas with the prospect of a long campaign in the [[Pacific War]].<ref name=\"history.state.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://history.state.gov/milestones/1945-1952/atomic |title=Milestones: 1945\u20131952 \u2013 Atomic Diplomacy |publisher=Office of the Historian, Bureau of Public Affairs, United States Department of State |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe detachment of [[Fleet Air Arm]] 772 Squadron, which had been responsible for operating the Chesapeakes, became 772B Squadron in May 1945 with the arrival of Boston 111s, [[F4U Corsair|Corsairs]] and [[de Havilland Mosquito]]es. The purpose of the Bostons was to train gunners from the naval air station at Ronaldsway, and [[Fairey Barracuda]]s were added to the scene as they brought in telegraphists to have air gunnery added to their training. However, this only lasted for a short period, as 772B was disbanded in September 1945 following the defeat of [[Japan]].<ref name=\"CT\"/><ref name=\"history.state.gov\"/>\n\n==Units==\nDuring the course of the operation of the station, the following units were at sometime based at RAF Andreas:\n\n10/41 to 03/42, 457 Sqn, with [[Supermarine Spitfire]]\n\n03/42 to 06/42, 452 Sqn, with Supermarine Spitfire\n\n06/42 to 09/42, 93 Sqn, with Supermarine Spitfire\n\n11/41 to 04/44, 275 Sqn (detachment), with [[Supermarine Walrus]] and [[Blackburn Skua]]\n\n04/45 to 05/45, 772 Sqn FAA (detachment), with [[Vought-Sikorsky Chesapeake]]\n\n05/45 TO 08/46, 772B Sqn FAA, with [[F4U Corsair|Corsairs]] and [[de Havilland Mosquito]]es\n\n05/43 to 09/46, No. 11 Air Gunnery School\n\n==Post-war and closure==\nBy the ending of hostilities in 1945 over 3,000 air gunners had successfully completed the air gunnery course at RAF Andreas.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nIn July 1946, the Douglas High School Flight of 506 Squadron [[Air Training Corps]], spent a week's camp at Andreas.<ref>''Isle of Man Examiner'', 9 August 1946.</ref> The squadron, together with 440, had been set up in the early years of the war to encourage the interest of schoolboys in the [[Royal Air Force]], many going on to train as aircrew. The cadets enjoyed daily flights in some of the Wellingtons at the station, taking advantage of what was now considerably quieter airspace over the north of the Island, as well as south west [[Scotland]] and [[Cumberland]].\n\n===At Home Day===\nAs was common amongst RAF Stations, Andreas staged an 'At Home Day' on Thursday May 9, 1946. A cricket match was held on the sport's field and in addition a speed dash was conducted by Spitfires and Mosquitoes.<ref>''Ramsey Courier.'' Friday, May 10, 1946; Page: 4</ref>\n\n===Battle of Britain Day===\nThe one and only opportunity the general public had of visiting Royal Air Force Andreas, was on [[Battle of Britain Day]], September 1946. It had already been announced that the station would close and that the Gunnery School would transfer to nearby Jurby. The Commanding Officer Group Captain Mackay, and the rest of the station personnel made every effort to show what the work of the station involved.[[File:Blackburn Skua L2923.png|thumb|The Blackburn Skua was operated by No. 275 Air Sea Rescue Squadron, which had a detachment based at RAF Andreas from October 1941.]] On show were the link trainer, parachute packing by the WAAFs and parachute dinghies and equipment used by the Andreas Rescue Station, which had so often been called upon in emergencies.\n\nThe following week the transfer of stores to [[RAF Jurby]] was completed, and the gates of Royal Air Force Andreas were finally closed.\n[[File:Andreas Airfield - Isle of Man - geograph.org.uk - 32328.jpg|thumb|right|The Watch Office ''circa'' 2012.]]\n\n==Subsequent use==\n===Civil Aerodrome===\nPost-war the situation of a civilian aerodrome was a foremost consideration for the government of the Isle of Man with Andreas at the time being generally regarded as the best aerodrome on the Island.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Ramsey Courier.'' Friday, September 07, 1945; Page: 4</ref> Situated on the northern plain it rarely suffered from [[fog]] as was often the case at [[Ronaldsway Airport]], particularly during the summer months, and the runways were considered superior to Ronaldsway.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> What did go against the development of Andreas into the Isle of Man's civil airport was its location with regard to its distance from the Island's capital, [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] ([[Ronaldsway Airport|Ronaldsway]] being 20 minutes drive as opposed to Andreas which was 50 minutes.)<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> This was the primary factor in the subsequent decision to continue to develop [[Ronaldsway Airport|Ronaldsway]], and just as had been the case a [[decade]] earlier with [[Hall Caine Airport]] the location of Andreas worked against it.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n[[File:Control Tower RAF Andreas.jpg|thumb|The Watch Office undergoing restoration, June 2018.]]\n\n===Missile base===\nFollowing the [[1957 Defence White Paper]] a further proposal for the use of Andreas airfield was to sell it back to the government of the [[United Kingdom]] in order for it to be developed into a [[Bristol Bloodhound]] [[Surface to Air Missile]] site for the [[RAF]].<ref>''Ramsey Courier.'' Friday, March 21, 1958; Page: 5</ref> The proposal was not proceeded with.\n\n===Infrastructure purchase===\nFollowing the station's closure steps were taken by the [[Isle of Man Government]], through the Local Government Board, to acquire three of the communal sites&nbsp;\u2013 the WAAF quarters, the hospital and sick quarters and a site in the centre of Andreas village&nbsp;\u2013 for the conversion into family accommodation. These were badly needed to re-house families living in condemned properties in [[Ramsey, Isle of Man|Ramsey]] and to relieve the general housing shortage on the Island as a consequence of the war. Every effort was made to convert the brick-built huts into acceptable two-and three-bedroom homes with electrically heated living rooms and kitchens. Each had a toilet installed, but bathrooms had to be shared. During 1947, a total of 81 families were accommodated as a temporary measure pending the construction of new housing estates. It was to be several years before such new housing was ready, and upon their completion, this temporary housing by now badly affected by damp, was demolished. One structure to survive, was the old gymnasium which still stands, and continues to provide the [[Andreas, Isle of Man|village of Andreas]] with a very useful Parish Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.justabouttravel.net/2013/02/01/andreas-parish-hall-isle-of-man-england-isle-of-man-canine-society-dog-show/ |title=Andreas Parish Hall , Isle of Man, England \u2013 Isle of Man Canine Society Dog Show |access-date=16 May 2017 |website=justabouttravel.net }}</ref><ref>''Mona's Herald'', 17 December 1946.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, negotiations between the Manx Government and the [[Air Ministry]] were proceeding as to the future of the airfield. [[Tynwald]], the Isle of Man's Parliament, accepted an offer to purchase the whole of the airfield for the price originally paid in compensation to the land owners&nbsp;\u2013 a total of \u00a323,750.<ref name=\"Man Examiner 1947\">''Isle of Man Examiner'', 24 October 1947.</ref> No charge was made for the buildings, the Air Ministry agreeing to this as a gesture of appreciation to the government and people of the [[Isle of Man]] for their co-operation during the early years of the war.<ref name=\"Man Examiner 1947\"/>\n\nThe airfield's runways were soon put to good use by the newly formed Andreas Racing Association for [[motorcycle racing]].  The Association's emblem is that of the  [[triskelion#Manx triskelion|Three Legs of Man]], set against the '''\"A\"''' layout of the airfield's runways.<ref name=\"Oliver2006p01\">{{Harvnb|Oliver|2006|p=01.}}</ref><ref>''The Green Final'',19 April 1947.</ref>\n[[File:Military graves at St Andrews Church, Andreas.jpg|thumb|right|Military graves at St Andrews Church, Andreas]]\n\nThe airfield was used on Saturday 25 June 1949, when unable to land at [[Ronaldsway Airport]] due to [[advection fog]] two Sivewirght Airways aircraft diverted to [[Andreas]]. The 28 passengers were in turn conveyed to [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] by motor coach.<ref>''Ramsey Courier'', 01.07.1949, page 4.</ref>\n[[File:Looking down Rwy 29 RAF Andreas.jpg|thumb|left|The view looking down Rwy 29 RAF Andreas (June 2018)]]\n\n===Current use===\nAfter a short time in the ownership of the Manx Government, the airfield was put up for sale as a complete entity, and was purchased by a Mr Morrey for the sum of \u00a333,000. The facility is still owned by the Morrey family, and many of its buildings still exist, being mostly used for storage. The local gliding club<ref name=\"Gliding for All on the Isle of Man\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manxgliding.org |title=Gliding for All on the Isle of Man |publisher=Andreas Gliding Club|access-date=2 May 2012}}</ref> still uses the airfield, together with a small number of privately owned light aircraft with the RAF Station now known as ''Andreas Airfield''.<ref name=\"Gliding for All on the Isle of Man\"/>\n\nTo this day, within easy view of the airfield, is the (still) stunted tower of the [[St Andrew's Church, Andreas, Isle of Man|parish church of St. Andrew]] (in [[Manx Gaelic]], Andrew translates to Andreas), a permanent legacy of Royal Air Force Station Andreas, and below which lie twenty-three military graves.<ref name=st-andrew /><ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://2ndww.blogspot.co.uk/2010/01/isle-of-man-during-world-war-two.html |title= The Isle of Man during World War Two |date=11 January 2010 |access-date=16 May 2017 |author=ritsonvaljos |website=2ndww.blogspot.co.uk }}</ref>\n\n==Accidents==\nAlthough not always involving aircraft based at the Isle of Man's air stations, there were some 200 air accidents on the Isle of Man during the course of the Second World War.<ref name=\"Poole2006p00\">{{Harvnb|Poole|2006|p=00.}}</ref> The actual number of accidents is open to conjecture as those only involving the loss of life are recorded. For every fatal crash, it is estimated that at least two others occurred many of which would include serious injury, while in others, the pilot and crew would escape unscathed.<ref name=\"Poole2006p00\"/>\n\n===Spitfire P8380===\nOn 1 December 1941 [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] MkII P8380, piloted by [[Flight Sergeant|Flt Sgt]] Gifford was returning to Andreas after an operational [[sortie]].<ref name=\"discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ww2talk.com/index.php?threads/tragic-fatal-accident-between-spitfire-and-lorry-andreas-airbase.50617/ |title=Tragic fatal accident between Spitfire and lorry Andreas airbase |date=17 November 2013 |access-date=16 May 2017 |author=DaveB |website=ww2talk.com }}</ref> Crossing the end of the runway at the time was one of the builder's foremen driving a lorry.  One of the Spitfire's wheels hit the cab of the lorry, causing severe injuries to its occupant, who was killed instantly.\n\n===Spitfire P7529===\nDuring operations on 3 December 1941, Spitfire P7529 piloted by [[Pilot Officer]] Edwards was involved in an incident whilst landing at Andreas. The aircraft's starboard wheel struck an obstacle whilst landing causing it to overturn. Whilst the pilot was uninjured, the aircraft was badly damaged, resulting in the pilot's log book being endorsed with red ink.<ref name=\"discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk\"/>\n\n===Spitfire P7502===\n[[File:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (8).jpg|right|90px|Flt Lt Edy]]The third accident within the same week at the beginning of December 1941, was of Spitfire P7502, piloted by [[Flight Lieutenant|Flt Lt]] Allen Edy [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]], commander of '''B Flight.'''\nFlt Lt Edy had departed Andreas at 15:25hrs, however 15 minutes later his aircraft crashed at Vondy's Farm, 3 miles from the airfield. Flt Lt Edy had managed to bale out, however he might well have been struck by part of the aircraft, causing him to become stunned and thereby lose his life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=154189 |title=Aircraft accident 05-Dec-1941 Supermarine Spitfire Mk IIa P7502 |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n* The engine of P7502 was recovered ''circa'' 1984 and is now on display at the Manx Aviation and Military Museum.\n\n===Spitfire BL351===\n[[File:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (12).jpg|right|90px|Sgt Pilot R. Goodhew]]On 8 May 1942, two of No. 452 Squadron's Spitfires were in collision over Andreas resulting in the death of Sergeant Pilot Reginald Goodhew. Sgt Goodhew, was flying Spitfire IIa (BL351)<ref>http://allspitfirepilots.org/pilots/1169</ref> and was involved in practicing camera quarter attacks with another Spitfire (AB244), piloted by [[Pilot Officer]] William Ford. The two aircraft collided head on, Pilot Officer Ford's aircraft crashed between the runways at Andreas, whilst Pilot Sergeant Goodhew's came down at Farrant Ford Farm. Pilot Officer Ford managed to bale out and survived. Sergeant Pilot Goodhew is buried in Andreas.<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p59\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=59.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spitfireassociation.com.au/goodhew-reginald-alan-2/ |title=Goodhew, Reginald 'Reg' Alan |access-date=16 May 2017 |publisher=The Spitfire Association |first1=Paul |last1=Carter |first2=Phil |last2=Listemann |first3=Vince |last3=Conant }}</ref>\n\n===Whitley BD417===\nOn 23 August 1942, the most memorable and tragic incident of the life of RAF Andreas occurred.  It was the day the station lost its [[Commanding Officer]], [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Edward Knowles.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/39/a4166039.shtml |title=Out of the blue \u2013 memories of the WAAF |first=Joyce |last=Brooke |publisher=BBC |date=8 June 2005 |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSaturday night had seen the usual revelry in the Moosejaw Bar of the Officer's Mess, attended by the Wing Commander.  Aged 33, and an experienced bomber pilot, he was considered a great \"''character''\" and reputedly knew how to make a party go with a swing, his prowess at the piano being put to good use.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe morning after, Wing Commander Knowles was back in the mess for what was described as a \"''convivial luncheon''\" with friends including Major Wait. Relaxing after [[luncheon]], news was received that an [[Armstrong-Whitworth Whitley]] had landed on the airfield, an unusual event which immediately aroused the interest of the C.O., who took his friends out onto the airfield to inspect the Whitley, which had called in to refuel before continuing on to a [[Coastal Command]] station in Scotland.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/> The [[Armstrong Whitworth Whitley|Whitley]] MkV, BD417 belonged to [[No. 296 Squadron RAF|296 Squadron]].<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://coptercrazy.brinkster.net/CVT-wings/waryears/AW38-Page2600.html |url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407231639/http://coptercrazy.brinkster.net/CVT-wings/waryears/AW38-Page2600.html |archive-date=7 April 2016 |title=AW-38 Production List |website=coptercrazy.brinkster.net |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/296squadron.cfm |title=296 Squadron |publisher=Royal Air Force |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThere was little else to do that summer's afternoon, and the Wing Commander decided to take the bomber up for a short flight.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n[[File:Armstrong Whitworth Whitley in flight c1940.jpg|thumb|Armstrong-Whitworth Whitley.]]\n\nObjections from the Whitley pilot were overruled and the duty pilot of the day, [[Flying Officer]] A. B. Paton, was prevailed upon to join the C.O., his two friends, and Thelma Knowles, Wing Commander Knowles' wife. Four  corporals from the nearby crash section found themselves joining the party and acting as ballast in the back of the aircraft.\nWith engines started, the C.O. followed the perimeter track to the south end of the northeasterly facing runway.\n\nThe Whitley slowly gathered speed but the end of the runway was reached before it became airborne. It was then seen to be in trouble as it tried to gain height in order to clear the Bride Hills looming ahead. This it failed to do, and it crashed heavily into a field of West Kimmeragh, bursting into flames, and sending up a pall of smoke which could be seen for miles around.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe rescue services went into immediate action but nothing could be done to save the four in the nose section of the aircraft; they all had been killed instantly.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe rear section of the [[fuselage]] broke open and the four corporals were seen staggering around dazed with shock. They were taken by ambulance to the station hospital, but one was transferred to the [[Military Hospital]] which had been established at the Majestic Hotel in [[Onchan]]. Sadly though, Corporal Henderson never recovered from his severe head wounds.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/>\n\nAn [[Air Ministry]] inquiry was ordered.\nThe five who perished in the disaster on that Sunday afternoon lie buried together in Andreas Churchyard.<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p60\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=60.}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{gallery\n|title= RAF Andreas\n|width=225 | height=170 | lines=3\n|align=centre\n|image:Plaque commemorating the donation of the organ to St Andrew's Church, Andreas.jpg|Plaque commemorating the donation of the organ blower to St Andrew's Church, Andreas.\n|image:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (15).jpg|The grave of Wing Commander Edward Vincent Knowles DFC.\n|image:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (16).jpg|The grave of Major Geoffrey Wait MC.\n|image:RAF Ensign in St Andrew's Church, Andreas.jpeg|RAF Ensign in St Andrew's Church, Andreas.\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Royal Air Force stations]]\n* [[RAF Jurby]]\n* [[RAF Jurby Head]], an offshore bombing range\n* [[54 Air-Sea Rescue Marine Craft Unit RAF]]\n* [[HMS Valkyrie (shore establishment)|HMS ''Valkyrie'']]\n* [[HMS St George (shore establishment)|HMS ''St George'']]\n* [[HMS Urley]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kniveton|1985}}|reference=Kniveton, G. ''Manx Aviation in War and Peace''. Douglas, Isle of Man, The Manx Experience, 1985.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Oliver|2006}}|reference=Oliver, Cpt W. ''Manx Festival of Aviation: Festival programme 2006''. Douglas, Isle of Man, The Manx Experience, 2006.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Halley|1988}}|reference=Halley, James J. ''The Squadrons of the Royal Air Force & Commonwealth, 1981\u20131988''. Tonbridge, Kent, UK: Air-Britain (Historians) Ltd., 1988. {{ISBN|0-85130-164-9}}.}}\n\n==External links==\n* [[Paddy Finucane|Paddy Finucane a celebrated pilot of No.452 Squadron RAAF]]\n{{Royal Air Force}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andreas}}\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations of World War II in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Airports in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1946]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name                = RAF Andreas\n| ensign              = Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg\n| nativename          = \n| nativename-a        = \n| nativename-r        = \n| image               = RAF roundel.svg\n| caption             = \n| IATA                = \n| ICAO                = \n| type                = Military\n| owner               = [[Air Ministry]]\n| operator            = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| city-served         = \n| location            = [[Andreas, Isle of Man|Andreas]], [[Isle of Man]]\n| built               = {{Start date|1940}}\n| used                = 1941-{{End date|1946}}\n| elevation-m         = 34\n| elevation-f         = {{Convert|34|m|disp=output number only|0}}\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|54|22|15|N|004|25|25|W|region:IM_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map         = Isle of Man\n| pushpin_label       = RAF Andreas\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Isle of Man\n| r1-number           = 06/24\n| r1-length-m         = 1000\n| r1-length-f         = 3280\n| r1-surface          = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number           = 11/29\n| r2-length-m         = 1000\n| r2-length-f         = 3280\n| r2-surface          = Asphalt\n| r3-number           = 17/35\n| r3-length-m         = 1000\n| r3-length-f         = 3280\n| r3-surface          = Asphalt\n| stat-year           = \n| stat1-header        = \n| stat1-data          = \n| stat2-header        = \n| stat2-data          = \n| footnotes           = Operational dates.<ref name=\"CT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.controltowers.co.uk/A/Andreas_Isle_of_Man.htm |title=RAF Andreas |publisher=Control Towers|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Royal Air Force Station Andreas''' or more simply '''RAF Andreas''' is a former [[Royal Air Force]] [[Royal Air Force station|station]] in the [[Isle of Man]] which was operational between 1941 and 1946.  It was built in fields between [[Andreas, Isle of Man|Andreas]] and [[Bride, Isle of Man|Bride]]. As was common practice, the station was named after the parish in which it was situated.<ref name=\"CT\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Construction===\nWhen the [[Luftwaffe]], in October 1940, began to attack British cities under the cover of darkness, the North West of England with its industrial centres and ports came within easy reach of German aircraft operating from [[occupied France]].  The first fighter squadron had arrived on the [[Isle of Man]] at nearby [[RAF Jurby]] in November 1940, and came under the control of the newly formed [[No. 9 Group RAF]], [[RAF Fighter Command|Fighter Command]].  Group Control was positioned at [[RAF Barton Hall]], near [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], and its sectors covered [[Lancashire]], [[Cheshire]] and [[Shropshire]].  Andreas was to be a separate sector with responsibility for the Irish Sea and its surrounds.  The new wing of [[Ramsey Grammar School]] was commissioned as Control Centre for the sector and was hastily prepared before the arrival of the new fighters at Jurby.  The Control Centre was linked to [[Chain Home|the three radar stations at Dalby, Scarlett and Bride]].<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p51\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=51.}}</ref>\n\nThe siting of a fighter airfield in the location of Andreas had been chosen because of its central location with regard to [[Liverpool]], [[Belfast]] and [[Glasgow]], as it was in an excellent position to provide protection to the vital shipping arriving at these ports. Finally, with the relevant compensation payments agreed, work on the construction of RAF Andreas began in earnest by the end of June 1940. A total of {{convert|500|acre}} of farmland was earmarked, {{convert|200|acre}} coming from both Ballaghaue Farm and Braust Farm, and a small portion of land was acquired which stretched into the adjacent parish of Bride.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturevannin.im/video_story_411491.html |title=World War Two (02) Defending the Island |publisher=[[Culture Vannin]] |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n[[File:Andreas Church (reduced tower).jpeg|thumb|left|[[St Andrew's Church, Andreas, Isle of Man|St Andrew's Church, Andreas]]. The tower was reduced on the request of the [[Air Ministry]] as it was seen as a danger to operations from the base.]]\nBy the spring of 1941 the airfield, to be built to the full specification of an operational fighter station, was beginning to take shape.  The main NE/SW runway was {{convert|1100|yd}} long and {{convert|50|yd}} wide and was obviously meant to take larger aircraft than fighters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forgottenairfields.com/united-kingdom/man/andreas-s961.html |title=Abandoned, Forgotten & Little Known Airfields in Europe: Andreas |website=forgottenairfields.com |author=Ronald V. |date=7 November 2010 |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>  From the perimeter track there was access to the flight dispersals in which a total of 24 blast pens (or E pens) were built, half to provide protection for the fighters while larger ones were for twin-engined aircraft.  Considerable thought had also gone into the airfield's defences, with the whole area being surrounded by {{convert|5|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} roller concertina barbed wire, with gaps located at the main entrance and crash gates<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p52\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=52.}}</ref> and by a [[tarmacadam]]ed perimeter track over three miles in distance.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Ramsey Courier, Friday, September 14, 1945; Page: 3</ref>\n\nRAF Andreas was designed as a dispersed airfield with many components of the base encompassed into the village of Andreas. The consequence of this was such that the domestic side and living quarters were a considerable distance from the technical side. There was also a dance and entertainments hall in the village and a farm on the Station.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nDuring the summer of 1941 the first RAF personnel arrived at Andreas.  This mainly consisted of a flight of [[Royal Air Force Police]], whose first duties were guarding the stores of supplies kept in the completed hangars.  Others arriving at that time included MT drivers and soldiers of the [[Wiltshire Regiment]], under the command of Major G.K. Wait [[Military Cross|MC]], who arrived to man the airfield's defences, along with the first of many [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force|WAAF]]s whose duties were to staff the administration offices and operations rooms. The station officially opened in August 1941, the first commanding officer of RAF Andreas being [[Group Captain]] J. Marson.<ref name=\"Man Times 1945\">''Isle of Man Times''. 14 September 1945.</ref>\n\n==Fighter Command==\n\n===Fighter Station===\n[[File:A Spitfire MkVb undergoing gun calibration at RAF Andreas, Isle of Man.jpg|thumb|A Spitfire MkVb of 457 Squadron undergoing gun calibration at RAF Andreas.]]\n\n===457 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 457 Squadron RAAF}}\n[[File:457 Squadron badge.jpeg.jpg|100px|left|457 Squadron badge.jpeg]]\nBy October 1941, RAF Andreas was ready to receive the first of [[No. 457 Squadron RAAF]] (457 Sqn)<ref name=\"ABCT\"/> Spitfires from [[RAF Jurby]] as a prelude to working up to operational efficiency.<ref name=\"Halley1988p478\">{{Harvnb|Halley|1988|p=478.}}</ref> This work-up would take six months, however the transfer of 457 Sqn's ground crew and administrative staff brought welcome relief to the congestion at [[Jurby]].<ref name=\"discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D8405567 |publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]] |title=Squadron Number: 457 RAAF (Royal Australian Air Force) |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref> It was also during this work-up period, that the [[Air Ministry]] insisted that the height of Andreas church tower be reduced, as it was a hazard, and in line with the southern end of the main runway.<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p55\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=55.}}</ref> The church tower was originally {{convert|120|ft}} high, and the most striking feature of the Island's northern plain being visible throughout the parish.<ref name=st-andrew>{{cite web |url=http://www.achurchnearyou.com/andreas-st-andrew/ |title=St Andrew, Andreas |publisher=[[The Church of England]] |website=achurchnearyou.com |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nRAF Andreas had become fully operational in March 1942, but by now 457 Sqn was ready to move south to join [[No. 11 Group RAF]] (11 Grp) at [[RAF Redhill]] and to take part in air strikes over northern [[France]].\n\n===452 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 452 Squadron RAAF}}\n[[File:452 Squadron RAAF Badge.jpg|70px|left|RAF312Sq]]Following the departure of 457 Squadron, it was immediately replaced by [[No. 452 Squadron RAAF]] (452 Sqn),<ref name=\"CT\"/> which had been formed in April 1941 and whose most celebrated pilot was the maverick Irishman, [[Paddy Finucane]].\n[[File:Ground Crew and pilot with Spitfire at RAF Andreas.png|thumb|right|Ground Crew and pilot with Spitfire at RAF Andreas]]\nIn June 1942, 452 Sqn's tenure at Andreas came to and end when the squadron returned to Australia,<ref name=\"awm.gov.au\">{{cite web |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/unit/U59437/ |title=No. 452 Squadron |publisher=Australian War Memorial |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref> sailing on 21 June, arriving in Melbourne on 13 August and re-assembled at [[RAAF Base Richmond|RAAF Richmond]], as [[No. 452 Squadron RAAF]], on 6 September.<ref name=\"awm.gov.au\"/><ref>https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/U59437</ref>\n\n===93 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 93 Squadron RAF}}\n[[File:Badge of No. 93 Squadron RAF.jpg|100px|left|RAF312Sq]]The third fighter unit to occupy RAF Andreas was [[No. 93 Squadron RAF]] (93 Sqn)<ref name=\"ABCT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/andreas |title=Andreas |publisher=Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust|access-date=29 April 2012}}</ref> which had an entirely different background, previously having been involved in the development of night fighter tactics using [[Douglas A-20 Havoc|Havoc]]s equipped with radar and [[Turbinlite]] searchlights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/93squadron.cfm |title=93 Squadron |publisher=Royal Air Force |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n93 Sqn reformed at Andreas as an entirely new squadron equipped with [[Spitfire]] VB's as it worked up to operational efficiency.<ref name=\"CT\"/><ref name=\"Halley1988p166\">{{Harvnb|Halley|1988|p=166.}}</ref> Considerable time was spent over the air-to-ground firing range along the Ayres coastline at Smeale which had been constructed not long after the first fighters had arrived at [[RAF Jurby]].  When Andreas airfield was under construction, the coastline north of Smeale had been heavily mined as a precaution against an enemy landing.  After four months, 93 Sqn was ready to move on to more direct action, and orders were received which would see the squadron re-locate to [[Algiers]] ready for the North African landings as part of [[Operation Torch]].<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p57\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=57.}}</ref>\n[[File:Supermarine Walrus.jpg|thumb|Supermarine Walrus]]\n\n===275 Squadron===\n{{main|No. 275 Squadron RAF}}\n[[File:No 275 Squadron Badge.png|80px|left|RAF312Sq]]In November 1941 RAF Andreas received a detachment from [[No. 275 Squadron RAF|275 Squadron]] (275 Sqn) which served as [[No. 9 Group RAF|9 Group's]] [[Air Sea Rescue]] Unit and which covered the [[Irish Sea]]. The Squadron had its administrative headquarters at [[RAF Valley]], [[Anglesey]],<ref name=\"CT\"/> and the detachment's [[Supermarine Walrus|Walrus amphibian Mk.I's]] were often to be seen flying around the Island.<ref name=\"Halley1988p342\">{{Harvnb|Halley|1988|p=342.}}</ref>\n\n===772 Squadron (FAA)===\n{{main|772 Naval Air Squadron}}\nAnother strange but permanent resident at Andreas, was a [[Vought-Sikorsky Chesapeake]] of the [[Fleet Air Arm]]. It belonged to [[772 Naval Air Squadron|772 Squadron]], [[Fleet Air Arm]] (772 Sqn),<ref name=\"ABCT\"/> and was employed to provide simulated conditions for the [[Royal Navy]]'s [[HMS Valkyrie (shore establishment)|No 1 Radar Training School]] which was situated on [[Douglas Head]]. The Chesapeake was replaced in October 1944, after crashing on Douglas Head, killing the pilot Sub Lieutenant R. S. Paton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manxgliding.org/features/andreasairfield/ |title=The History of Andreas Airfield  |publisher=Andreas Gliding Club |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n[[File:E pen RAF Andreas.jpg|thumb|An E-pen at RAF Andreas (2018). These were situated predominately on the eastern and northern side of the airfield and were designed to afford shelter from attack for aircraft and ground crew. Two aircraft could be accommodated within the pen. Today, this one houses a mobile phone mast.]]\n\n==Operations==\nAt night the drone of [[bomber]]s could be heard as they passed overhead on their way to Belfast. These were the nights when the fighters based at RAF Andreas and RAF Jurby were called into action.\n[[Radar in World War II|Airborne radar]] was still in its infancy, and there was little they could do except offer token resistance.\nOccasionally, and enemy aircraft would be sighted and in the ensuing chase bombs would be jettisoned as the [[Heinkel He 111|Heinkel]] or [[Dornier Do 17|Dornier]] made a rapid escape.\nThe [[air raid siren]]s of the Island sounded a total of 43 alerts&nbsp;\u2013 32 of them in 1942. Many were of a short duration, but on the nights of 20 and 21 December 1941, there were two alerts each lasting five hours when Liverpool and Manchester were being heavily attacked.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://liverpoolremembrance.weebly.com/christmas-blitz.html |title=Liverpool And Merseyside Remembered: Christmas Blitz |website=liverpoolremembrance.weebly.com |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/history/the-blitz-around-britain |title=The Blitz Around Britain |publisher=Imperial War Museums |first=Amanda |last=Mason |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe first enemy bomb to fall on the Isle of Man was on 18 September 1940, when [[high explosive]] bombs caused four large craters in the [[Dalby, Isle of Man|Dalby]] area&nbsp;\u2013 without damage or injury.<ref name=\"culturevannin.im\">{{cite web |url=http://www.culturevannin.im/video_story_411547.html |title=World War Two (09) Bombs in the Island |publisher=Culture Vannin |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\nOn the nights of 7, 15, and 16 April 1941, enemy bombers were again over the Island. On the first occasion the Island was illuminated with [[Flare (pyrotechnic)|flare]]s and [[incendiary bomb]]s landed near [[Port Soderick]].\nOn the 15th a high explosive bomb landed close to Cronk Ruagh [[Sanatorium]] near Ramsey. [[Shrapnel shell|Shrapnel]] landed on the entrance steps and windows were blown out.\nThe following night more H.E. bombs fell at [[Castletown, Isle of Man|Scarlett]] narrowly missing the [[Chain Home|Radar Station]].<ref name=\"culturevannin.im\"/>\n\nThe following month considerable alarm was caused when bombs fell on the outskirts of [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vimeo.com/129460328 |title=9. Bombing: The Second World War in the Isle of Man |publisher=Culture Vannin |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref> It was the night of 8/9 May, when clear conditions prevailed and when [[Bombing of Dublin in World War II|Dublin was mistakenly bombed]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/why-the-nazis-bombed-dublin-1075966.html |title=Why the Nazis bombed Dublin |last=Fisk |first=Robert |date=24 January 1999 |access-date=16 May 2017 |newspaper=The Independent16  }}</ref>\n\nAfter 93 Sqn had exchanged the sands of the Ayres for the sands of North Africa, the station grew quiet and much of it was reduced to care and maintenance. There was little to do for [[No. 9 Group RAF|9 Group]] now that the emergencies which had brought it into being had largely passed. Nevertheless, RAF Andreas remained officially part of 9 Group until August 1944, [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Raynor being responsible for the signing and despatch of the operational orders which signalled the disbanding of the Group, and many of the 900 airmen and 400 WAAFs were posted out whilst new plans were awaited for the Station.\n\nOne of the residents who did not leave was the detachment from [[No. 275 Squadron RAF|275 Squadron]] which would stay at the Station until the end of April, 1944.<ref name=\"CT\"/>\n\nDuring the spring of 1943, a new role was found for the excellent facilities at Andreas, and preparations began to set up '''No.11 Air Gunnery School of [[RAF Training Command|Training Command]]'''.<ref name=\"CT\"/>\n\n==Training Command==\n\n===No.11 Air Gunnery School===\nWith the specialisation required in aircrew for the heavy bombers of [[RAF Bomber Command|Bomber Command]], air gunners became a separate category. Each [[Avro Lancaster]] and [[Handley Page Halifax]] required two or three gunners in its crew, so thousands would be required to meet the demands of the growing strategic offensive and to replace losses.\n\nRAF Andreas was to play an important role in the training programme, and thus began the busiest period in the life of the station. The Station's new commanding officer was Group Captain Mackay, who would remain at Andreas for the rest of the war period, and the station completely changed in character from that of a fighter station to that of a training establishment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rafcommands.com/archive/09815.php |title=Air Gunnery Schools |publisher=Royal Air Force Commands |access-date=16 May 2017 |first=Tom |last=Williams |date=19 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\nWhilst at Andreas, the volunteer pupils selected for air gunners underwent an intensive ten-week course, before passing on to the operational training units of [[RAF Bomber Command]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~nbpennfi/penn8b1ADemandingTrainingRegime.htm |title=A Demanding Training Regime |website=rootsweb.ancestry.com |access-date=16 May 2017 |first=G. Christian |last=Larsen |publisher=Pennfield Parish Military Historical Society }}</ref> The course involved sighting; aircraft recognition; pyrotechnics; clay-pigeon and 25 yard range shoots; care and maintenance of .303 and .5 Browning machine guns and 20mm cannon; turret hydraulics, manipulation and operation, and the use of cine-camera guns. The training huts were equipped with the various types of turrets then in use, including [[Boulton Paul Aircraft|Boulton Paul]] Types A and F, and [[Frazer Nash]] 121 which were installed in the [[Handley Page Halifax]] and [[Avro Lancaster]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pilotfriend.com/photo_albums/timeline/ww2/Avro%20Lancaster.htm |title=Avro Lancaster |publisher=PilotFriend |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe first aircraft to arrive were 15 [[Avro Anson]] gunnery trainers. For more advanced experience, training was conducted on a succession of [[Vickers Wellington]]s which were being withdrawn from the front-line squadrons of Bomber Command, and target towing duties were the responsibility of [[Bristol Mercury]] engined [[Miles Martinet]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aviastar.org/air/england/miles_m-25.php |title=Miles M.25 Martinet  |access-date=16 May 2017 |website=aviastar.org \u2013 All the World's Rotorcraft }}</ref>\n[[File:Miles Martinet.jpg|thumb|right|Martinet in RAF service]]\nFiring took place in allotted zones over the sea on both sides of the Point of Ayre, care being taken not to interfere with the Jurby bombing ranges.<ref name=\"Man Times 1945\"/>\n[[File:Vickers Wellington - RAF Bomber Command HU108373.jpg|thumb|Vickers Wellington]]\nDespite the continual flying programme over the congested north of the Island, accidents involving Andreas aircraft proved to be very rare, and only one documented incident resulted in the loss of a life. During 1944, Andreas, because of the length of its main runway, became an emergency landing ground for the Atlantic ferry route and was occasionally used by American aircraft such as the [[B-17 Flying Fortress]] and the [[B-24 Liberator]].<ref name=\"Man Times 1945\"/> The ending of the war in [[Europe]] in May 1945, saw no let up in the routine at Andreas with the prospect of a long campaign in the [[Pacific War]].<ref name=\"history.state.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://history.state.gov/milestones/1945-1952/atomic |title=Milestones: 1945\u20131952 \u2013 Atomic Diplomacy |publisher=Office of the Historian, Bureau of Public Affairs, United States Department of State |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe detachment of [[Fleet Air Arm]] 772 Squadron, which had been responsible for operating the Chesapeakes, became 772B Squadron in May 1945 with the arrival of Boston 111s, [[F4U Corsair|Corsairs]] and [[de Havilland Mosquito]]es. The purpose of the Bostons was to train gunners from the naval air station at Ronaldsway, and [[Fairey Barracuda]]s were added to the scene as they brought in telegraphists to have air gunnery added to their training. However, this only lasted for a short period, as 772B was disbanded in September 1945 following the defeat of [[Japan]].<ref name=\"CT\"/><ref name=\"history.state.gov\"/>\n\n==Units==\nDuring the course of the operation of the station, the following units were at sometime based at RAF Andreas:\n\n10/41 to 03/42, 457 Sqn, with [[Supermarine Spitfire]]\n\n03/42 to 06/42, 452 Sqn, with Supermarine Spitfire\n\n06/42 to 09/42, 93 Sqn, with Supermarine Spitfire\n\n11/41 to 04/44, 275 Sqn (detachment), with [[Supermarine Walrus]] and [[Blackburn Skua]]\n\n04/45 to 05/45, 772 Sqn FAA (detachment), with [[Vought-Sikorsky Chesapeake]]\n\n05/45 TO 08/46, 772B Sqn FAA, with [[F4U Corsair|Corsairs]] and [[de Havilland Mosquito]]es\n\n05/43 to 09/46, No. 11 Air Gunnery School\n\n==Post-war and closure==\nBy the ending of hostilities in 1945 over 3,000 air gunners had successfully completed the air gunnery course at RAF Andreas.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nIn July 1946, the Douglas High School Flight of 506 Squadron [[Air Training Corps]], spent a week's camp at Andreas.<ref>''Isle of Man Examiner'', 9 August 1946.</ref> The squadron, together with 440, had been set up in the early years of the war to encourage the interest of schoolboys in the [[Royal Air Force]], many going on to train as aircrew. The cadets enjoyed daily flights in some of the Wellingtons at the station, taking advantage of what was now considerably quieter airspace over the north of the Island, as well as south west [[Scotland]] and [[Cumberland]].\n\n===At Home Day===\nAs was common amongst RAF Stations, Andreas staged an 'At Home Day' on Thursday May 9, 1946. A cricket match was held on the sport's field and in addition a speed dash was conducted by Spitfires and Mosquitoes.<ref>''Ramsey Courier.'' Friday, May 10, 1946; Page: 4</ref>\n\n===Battle of Britain Day===\nThe one and only opportunity the general public had of visiting Royal Air Force Andreas, was on [[Battle of Britain Day]], September 1946. It had already been announced that the station would close and that the Gunnery School would transfer to nearby Jurby. The Commanding Officer Group Captain Mackay, and the rest of the station personnel made every effort to show what the work of the station involved.[[File:Blackburn Skua L2923.png|thumb|The Blackburn Skua was operated by No. 275 Air Sea Rescue Squadron, which had a detachment based at RAF Andreas from October 1941.]] On show were the link trainer, parachute packing by the WAAFs and parachute dinghies and equipment used by the Andreas Rescue Station, which had so often been called upon in emergencies.\n\nThe following week the transfer of stores to [[RAF Jurby]] was completed, and the gates of Royal Air Force Andreas were finally closed.\n[[File:Andreas Airfield - Isle of Man - geograph.org.uk - 32328.jpg|thumb|right|The Watch Office ''circa'' 2012.]]\n\n==Subsequent use==\n===Civil Aerodrome===\nPost-war the situation of a civilian aerodrome was a foremost consideration for the government of the Isle of Man with Andreas at the time being generally regarded as the best aerodrome on the Island.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Ramsey Courier.'' Friday, September 07, 1945; Page: 4</ref> Situated on the northern plain it rarely suffered from [[fog]] as was often the case at [[Ronaldsway Airport]], particularly during the summer months, and the runways were considered superior to Ronaldsway.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> What did go against the development of Andreas into the Isle of Man's civil airport was its location with regard to its distance from the Island's capital, [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] ([[Ronaldsway Airport|Ronaldsway]] being 20 minutes drive as opposed to Andreas which was 50 minutes.)<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> This was the primary factor in the subsequent decision to continue to develop [[Ronaldsway Airport|Ronaldsway]], and just as had been the case a [[decade]] earlier with [[Hall Caine Airport]] the location of Andreas worked against it.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n[[File:Control Tower RAF Andreas.jpg|thumb|The Watch Office undergoing restoration, June 2018.]]\n\n===Missile base===\nFollowing the [[1957 Defence White Paper]] a further proposal for the use of Andreas airfield was to sell it back to the government of the [[United Kingdom]] in order for it to be developed into a [[Bristol Bloodhound]] [[Surface to Air Missile]] site for the [[RAF]].<ref>''Ramsey Courier.'' Friday, March 21, 1958; Page: 5</ref> The proposal was not proceeded with.\n\n===Infrastructure purchase===\nFollowing the station's closure steps were taken by the [[Isle of Man Government]], through the Local Government Board, to acquire three of the communal sites&nbsp;\u2013 the WAAF quarters, the hospital and sick quarters and a site in the centre of Andreas village&nbsp;\u2013 for the conversion into family accommodation. These were badly needed to re-house families living in condemned properties in [[Ramsey, Isle of Man|Ramsey]] and to relieve the general housing shortage on the Island as a consequence of the war. Every effort was made to convert the brick-built huts into acceptable two-and three-bedroom homes with electrically heated living rooms and kitchens. Each had a toilet installed, but bathrooms had to be shared. During 1947, a total of 81 families were accommodated as a temporary measure pending the construction of new housing estates. It was to be several years before such new housing was ready, and upon their completion, this temporary housing by now badly affected by damp, was demolished. One structure to survive, was the old gymnasium which still stands, and continues to provide the [[Andreas, Isle of Man|village of Andreas]] with a very useful Parish Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.justabouttravel.net/2013/02/01/andreas-parish-hall-isle-of-man-england-isle-of-man-canine-society-dog-show/ |title=Andreas Parish Hall , Isle of Man, England \u2013 Isle of Man Canine Society Dog Show |access-date=16 May 2017 |website=justabouttravel.net }}</ref><ref>''Mona's Herald'', 17 December 1946.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, negotiations between the Manx Government and the [[Air Ministry]] were proceeding as to the future of the airfield. [[Tynwald]], the Isle of Man's Parliament, accepted an offer to purchase the whole of the airfield for the price originally paid in compensation to the land owners&nbsp;\u2013 a total of \u00a323,750.<ref name=\"Man Examiner 1947\">''Isle of Man Examiner'', 24 October 1947.</ref> No charge was made for the buildings, the Air Ministry agreeing to this as a gesture of appreciation to the government and people of the [[Isle of Man]] for their co-operation during the early years of the war.<ref name=\"Man Examiner 1947\"/>\n\nThe airfield's runways were soon put to good use by the newly formed Andreas Racing Association for [[motorcycle racing]].  The Association's emblem is that of the  [[triskelion#Manx triskelion|Three Legs of Man]], set against the '''\"A\"''' layout of the airfield's runways.<ref name=\"Oliver2006p01\">{{Harvnb|Oliver|2006|p=01.}}</ref><ref>''The Green Final'',19 April 1947.</ref>\n[[File:Military graves at St Andrews Church, Andreas.jpg|thumb|right|Military graves at St Andrews Church, Andreas]]\n\nThe airfield was used on Saturday 25 June 1949, when unable to land at [[Ronaldsway Airport]] due to [[advection fog]] two Sivewirght Airways aircraft diverted to [[Andreas]]. The 28 passengers were in turn conveyed to [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] by motor coach.<ref>''Ramsey Courier'', 01.07.1949, page 4.</ref>\n[[File:Looking down Rwy 29 RAF Andreas.jpg|thumb|left|The view looking down Rwy 29 RAF Andreas (June 2018)]]\n\n===Current use===\nAfter a short time in the ownership of the Manx Government, the airfield was put up for sale as a complete entity, and was purchased by a Mr Morrey for the sum of \u00a333,000. The facility is still owned by the Morrey family, and many of its buildings still exist, being mostly used for storage. The local gliding club<ref name=\"Gliding for All on the Isle of Man\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manxgliding.org |title=Gliding for All on the Isle of Man |publisher=Andreas Gliding Club|access-date=2 May 2012}}</ref> still uses the airfield, together with a small number of privately owned light aircraft with the RAF Station now known as ''Andreas Airfield''.<ref name=\"Gliding for All on the Isle of Man\"/>\n\nTo this day, within easy view of the airfield, is the (still) stunted tower of the [[St Andrew's Church, Andreas, Isle of Man|parish church of St. Andrew]] (in [[Manx Gaelic]], Andrew translates to Andreas), a permanent legacy of Royal Air Force Station Andreas, and below which lie twenty-three military graves.<ref name=st-andrew /><ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://2ndww.blogspot.co.uk/2010/01/isle-of-man-during-world-war-two.html |title= The Isle of Man during World War Two |date=11 January 2010 |access-date=16 May 2017 |author=ritsonvaljos |website=2ndww.blogspot.co.uk }}</ref>\n\n==Accidents==\nAlthough not always involving aircraft based at the Isle of Man's air stations, there were some 200 air accidents on the Isle of Man during the course of the Second World War.<ref name=\"Poole2006p00\">{{Harvnb|Poole|2006|p=00.}}</ref> The actual number of accidents is open to conjecture as those only involving the loss of life are recorded. For every fatal crash, it is estimated that at least two others occurred many of which would include serious injury, while in others, the pilot and crew would escape unscathed.<ref name=\"Poole2006p00\"/>\n\n===Spitfire P8380===\nOn 1 December 1941 [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] MkII P8380, piloted by [[Flight Sergeant|Flt Sgt]] Gifford was returning to Andreas after an operational [[sortie]].<ref name=\"discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ww2talk.com/index.php?threads/tragic-fatal-accident-between-spitfire-and-lorry-andreas-airbase.50617/ |title=Tragic fatal accident between Spitfire and lorry Andreas airbase |date=17 November 2013 |access-date=16 May 2017 |author=DaveB |website=ww2talk.com }}</ref> Crossing the end of the runway at the time was one of the builder's foremen driving a lorry.  One of the Spitfire's wheels hit the cab of the lorry, causing severe injuries to its occupant, who was killed instantly.\n\n===Spitfire P7529===\nDuring operations on 3 December 1941, Spitfire P7529 piloted by [[Pilot Officer]] Edwards was involved in an incident whilst landing at Andreas. The aircraft's starboard wheel struck an obstacle whilst landing causing it to overturn. Whilst the pilot was uninjured, the aircraft was badly damaged, resulting in the pilot's log book being endorsed with red ink.<ref name=\"discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk\"/>\n\n===Spitfire P7502===\n[[File:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (8).jpg|right|90px|Flt Lt Edy]]The third accident within the same week at the beginning of December 1941, was of Spitfire P7502, piloted by [[Flight Lieutenant|Flt Lt]] Allen Edy [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]], commander of '''B Flight.'''\nFlt Lt Edy had departed Andreas at 15:25hrs, however 15 minutes later his aircraft crashed at Vondy's Farm, 3 miles from the airfield. Flt Lt Edy had managed to bale out, however he might well have been struck by part of the aircraft, causing him to become stunned and thereby lose his life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=154189 |title=Aircraft accident 05-Dec-1941 Supermarine Spitfire Mk IIa P7502 |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n* The engine of P7502 was recovered ''circa'' 1984 and is now on display at the Manx Aviation and Military Museum.\n\n===Spitfire BL351===\n[[File:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (12).jpg|right|90px|Sgt Pilot R. Goodhew]]On 8 May 1942, two of No. 452 Squadron's Spitfires were in collision over Andreas resulting in the death of Sergeant Pilot Reginald Goodhew. Sgt Goodhew, was flying Spitfire IIa (BL351)<ref>http://allspitfirepilots.org/pilots/1169</ref> and was involved in practicing camera quarter attacks with another Spitfire (AB244), piloted by [[Pilot Officer]] William Ford. The two aircraft collided head on, Pilot Officer Ford's aircraft crashed between the runways at Andreas, whilst Pilot Sergeant Goodhew's came down at Farrant Ford Farm. Pilot Officer Ford managed to bale out and survived. Sergeant Pilot Goodhew is buried in Andreas.<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p59\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=59.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spitfireassociation.com.au/goodhew-reginald-alan-2/ |title=Goodhew, Reginald 'Reg' Alan |access-date=16 May 2017 |publisher=The Spitfire Association |first1=Paul |last1=Carter |first2=Phil |last2=Listemann |first3=Vince |last3=Conant }}</ref>\n\n===Whitley BD417===\nOn 23 August 1942, the most memorable and tragic incident of the life of RAF Andreas occurred.  It was the day the station lost its [[Commanding Officer]], [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Edward Knowles.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/39/a4166039.shtml |title=Out of the blue \u2013 memories of the WAAF |first=Joyce |last=Brooke |publisher=BBC |date=8 June 2005 |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSaturday night had seen the usual revelry in the Moosejaw Bar of the Officer's Mess, attended by the Wing Commander.  Aged 33, and an experienced bomber pilot, he was considered a great \"''character''\" and reputedly knew how to make a party go with a swing, his prowess at the piano being put to good use.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe morning after, Wing Commander Knowles was back in the mess for what was described as a \"''convivial luncheon''\" with friends including Major Wait. Relaxing after [[luncheon]], news was received that an [[Armstrong-Whitworth Whitley]] had landed on the airfield, an unusual event which immediately aroused the interest of the C.O., who took his friends out onto the airfield to inspect the Whitley, which had called in to refuel before continuing on to a [[Coastal Command]] station in Scotland.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/> The [[Armstrong Whitworth Whitley|Whitley]] MkV, BD417 belonged to [[No. 296 Squadron RAF|296 Squadron]].<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://coptercrazy.brinkster.net/CVT-wings/waryears/AW38-Page2600.html |url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407231639/http://coptercrazy.brinkster.net/CVT-wings/waryears/AW38-Page2600.html |archive-date=7 April 2016 |title=AW-38 Production List |website=coptercrazy.brinkster.net |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/296squadron.cfm |title=296 Squadron |publisher=Royal Air Force |access-date=16 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThere was little else to do that summer's afternoon, and the Wing Commander decided to take the bomber up for a short flight.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n[[File:Armstrong Whitworth Whitley in flight c1940.jpg|thumb|Armstrong-Whitworth Whitley.]]\n\nObjections from the Whitley pilot were overruled and the duty pilot of the day, [[Flying Officer]] A. B. Paton, was prevailed upon to join the C.O., his two friends, and Thelma Knowles, Wing Commander Knowles' wife. Four  corporals from the nearby crash section found themselves joining the party and acting as ballast in the back of the aircraft.\nWith engines started, the C.O. followed the perimeter track to the south end of the northeasterly facing runway.\n\nThe Whitley slowly gathered speed but the end of the runway was reached before it became airborne. It was then seen to be in trouble as it tried to gain height in order to clear the Bride Hills looming ahead. This it failed to do, and it crashed heavily into a field of West Kimmeragh, bursting into flames, and sending up a pall of smoke which could be seen for miles around.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe rescue services went into immediate action but nothing could be done to save the four in the nose section of the aircraft; they all had been killed instantly.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe rear section of the [[fuselage]] broke open and the four corporals were seen staggering around dazed with shock. They were taken by ambulance to the station hospital, but one was transferred to the [[Military Hospital]] which had been established at the Majestic Hotel in [[Onchan]]. Sadly though, Corporal Henderson never recovered from his severe head wounds.<ref name=\"2ndww.blogspot.co.uk\"/>\n\nAn [[Air Ministry]] inquiry was ordered.\nThe five who perished in the disaster on that Sunday afternoon lie buried together in Andreas Churchyard.<ref name=\"Kniveton1985p60\">{{Harvnb|Kniveton|1985|p=60.}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{gallery\n|title= RAF Andreas\n|width=225 | height=170 | lines=3\n|align=centre\n|image:Plaque commemorating the donation of the organ to St Andrew's Church, Andreas.jpg|Plaque commemorating the donation of the organ blower to St Andrew's Church, Andreas.\n|image:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (15).jpg|The grave of Wing Commander Edward Vincent Knowles DFC.\n|image:St Andrew's Church, Andreas (16).jpg|The grave of Major Geoffrey Wait MC.\n|image:RAF Ensign in St Andrew's Church, Andreas.jpeg|RAF Ensign in St Andrew's Church, Andreas.\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Royal Air Force stations]]\n* [[RAF Jurby]]\n* [[RAF Jurby Head]], an offshore bombing range\n* [[54 Air-Sea Rescue Marine Craft Unit RAF]]\n* [[HMS Valkyrie (shore establishment)|HMS ''Valkyrie'']]\n* [[HMS St George (shore establishment)|HMS ''St George'']]\n* [[HMS Urley]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kniveton|1985}}|reference=Kniveton, G. ''Manx Aviation in War and Peace''. Douglas, Isle of Man, The Manx Experience, 1985.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Oliver|2006}}|reference=Oliver, Cpt W. ''Manx Festival of Aviation: Festival programme 2006''. Douglas, Isle of Man, The Manx Experience, 2006.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Halley|1988}}|reference=Halley, James J. ''The Squadrons of the Royal Air Force & Commonwealth, 1981\u20131988''. Tonbridge, Kent, UK: Air-Britain (Historians) Ltd., 1988. {{ISBN|0-85130-164-9}}.}}\n\n==External links==\n* [[Paddy Finucane|Paddy Finucane a celebrated pilot of No.452 Squadron RAAF]]\n{{Royal Air Force}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andreas}}\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations of World War II in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Airports in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1946]]\n", "name_user": "Harvey Milligan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTraining Command", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RAF_Andreas"}
{"title_page": "Kalle Nieminen", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| image            = Kalle Nieminen 1909.png\n| caption          = Kalle Nieminen in 1909\n| name             = Kalle Nieminen\n| full_name        = Karl Maurits Nieminen\n| nickname         = Kaarlo, Kalle\n| national_team    = Finland\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1878|04|26}}\n| birth_place      = Asikkala, Grand Duchy of Finland, Russian Empire\n| death_date       = 1946 (aged 68)\n| death_place      = United States\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments        = \n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = Long distance runner and coach, stonemason, masseur, fox farmer\n| years_active     = 1903\u20131910s\n| employer         = \n| agent            = \n| height           = 171 cm\n| weight           = 70 kg\n| spouse           = Maria B\u00e4ck\n| life_partner     = \n| other_interests  = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n| <!-- Sport -->\n| sport            = [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n| event            = [[Long-distance running]]\n| universityteam   = \n| collegeteam      = \n| league           = \n| league_type      = \n| club             = {{Unbulleted list|[[Helsingin Koitto]] (1903\u20131905)|[[Helsingin Reipas]] (1905\u20131908)|[[Helsingin Jyry]] (1908\u20131909)}}\n| turnedpro        = 1910\n| partner          = \n| former_partner   = \n| coach            = \n| retired          = \n| coaching         = \n| module2          = \n| <!-- Achievements and titles -->\n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| pb               = {{unbulleted list|Marathon: 2:43:10 (1912)}}\n| <!-- Medal record -->\n| show-medals      = \n| medaltemplates   = \n| medaltemplates-title = \n| module3          = \n}}\n'''Karl Maurits \"Kalle\" Nieminen''' (26 April 1878 &ndash; 1946) was a Finnish long-distance runner, who competed in the [[1908 Summer Olympics]].\n\nHe was born in [[Asikkala]], [[Grand Duchy of Finland]], [[Russian Empire]], the eighth child of Kalle (1835\u20131911) and Vilhelmiina Nieminen (1842\u20131918) in Ven\u00e4j\u00e4nniemi, Asikkala in 1878. He moved to [[Helsinki]] at the age of 21, where he worked as a stonemason.<ref name=\"sukutarina\">{{cite book | last1 = Halme | first1 = Seija | chapter = Sukutarina pitk\u00e4nmatkanjuoksuna: Ven\u00e4j\u00e4nniemi \u2013 Helsinki \u2013 New York | editor1-last= Roiko-Jokela | editor1-first = Heikki | editor2-last = Sironen | editor2-first = Esa | editor3-last = Viita | editor3-first = Ossi | title = Taidetta ja tehdasurheilua |series = Suomen urheiluhistoriallisen seuran vuosikirja | language = fi | volume = 2005 | location = Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 | publisher = Atena | publication-date = 2005 | pages = 39\u201347 | isbn = 951-796-414-5 | issn = 1237-3133 }}</ref>\n\nHe participated in his first race in 1903, when the longest ones held were [[Middle-distance running|middle-distance events]]. He became that year a member of the club [[Helsingin Koitto]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Vettenniemi | first1 = Erkki | year = 2006 | title = Joutavan juoksun j\u00e4ljill\u00e4. Kest\u00e4vyysjuoksun varhaisvaiheet Suomessa | trans-title = In Pursuit of Idle Running. The Early History of Long-Distance Running in Finland | series = Historiallisia tutkimuksia | language = fi | volume = 226 | location = Helsinki | publisher = Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura | page = 279 | isbn = 951-746-736-2 | issn = 0073-2559 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 1905 he won a [[10,000 metres|10,000 metre race]] with a Finnish record time 37:44.6.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Vettenniemi | first1 = Erkki | year = 2006 | title = Joutavan juoksun j\u00e4ljill\u00e4. Kest\u00e4vyysjuoksun varhaisvaiheet Suomessa | trans-title = In Pursuit of Idle Running. The Early History of Long-Distance Running in Finland | series = Historiallisia tutkimuksia | language = fi | volume = 226 | location = Helsinki | publisher = Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura | pages = 304\u2013305 | isbn = 951-746-736-2 | issn = 0073-2559 }}</ref> Soon he changed to the club [[Helsingin Reipas]]. On 16 September 1906, he won the first [[Marathon|marathon race]] held in Finland.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nIn September 1907, he had his first races abroad. In Stockholm, he tied the Finnish [[one hour run]] record with 16,759 meters, but at the time only races in Finland counted towards the record.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nIn 1908 he changed clubs to [[Helsingin Jyry]], where he also coached junior athletes. In May he won the Olympic selection marathon race and represented Finland at the [[Athletics at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's marathon|1908 Olympic marathon]], where he finished tenth with a time 3:09:50.8.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nHe ran his last race in Finland in August 1909, after which he emigrated to the United States to compete professionally.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nHis first professional race was in [[Philadelphia]] on 28 March 1910, when he won a two-man tag team relay marathon with [[William Kolehmainen]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Vettenniemi | first1 = Erkki | year = 2014 | title = Suomalaisen kest\u00e4vyysjuoksun historia | language = fi | location = Helsinki | publisher = Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura | page = 23 | isbn = 978-952-222-451-4 }}</ref>\n\nHis marathon personal best was 2:43:10, which he ran in [[Vailsburg, Newark]] in October 1912.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nAfter retirement, he coached long-distance runners in [[Columbia University]]. He also earned a living as a masseur and a fox farmer.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nHe made his last contact to his native Finland in the early 1920s, when he visited his sister's family in Asikkala. He died at the age of 68 in the United States in 1946. The news was not transmitted to anyone in Finland, where he was declared dead in absentia in 1971.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nieminen, Kalle}}\n[[Category:Finnish male marathon runners]]\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Asikkala]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of Finland]]\n[[Category:Finnish emigrants to the United States (1809\u20131917)]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1908 Summer Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| image            = Kalle Nieminen 1909.png\n| caption          = Kalle Nieminen in 1909\n| name             = Kalle Nieminen\n| full_name        = Karl Maurits Nieminen\n| nickname         = Kaarlo, Kalle\n| national_team    = Finland\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1878|04|26}}\n| birth_place      = Asikkala, Grand Duchy of Finland, Russian Empire\n| death_date       = 1946 (aged 68)\n| death_place      = United States\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments        = \n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = Long distance runner and coach, stonemason, masseur, fox farmer\n| years_active     = 1903\u20131910s\n| employer         = \n| agent            = \n| height           = 171 cm\n| weight           = 70 kg\n| spouse           = Maria B\u00e4ck\n| life_partner     = \n| other_interests  = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n| <!-- Sport -->\n| sport            = [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n| event            = [[Long-distance running]]\n| universityteam   = \n| collegeteam      = \n| league           = \n| league_type      = \n| club             = {{Unbulleted list|[[Helsingin Koitto]] (1903\u20131905)|[[Helsingin Reipas]] (1905\u20131908)|[[Helsingin Jyry]] (1908\u20131909)}}\n| turnedpro        = 1910\n| partner          = \n| former_partner   = \n| coach            = \n| retired          = \n| coaching         = \n| module2          = \n| <!-- Achievements and titles -->\n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| pb               = {{unbulleted list|Marathon: 2:43:10 (1912)}}\n| <!-- Medal record -->\n| show-medals      = \n| medaltemplates   = \n| medaltemplates-title = \n| module3          = \n}}\n'''Karl Maurits \"Kalle\" Nieminen''' (26 April 1878 &ndash; 1946) was a Finnish long-distance runner, who competed in the [[1908 Summer Olympics]].\n\nHe was born in [[Asikkala]], [[Grand Duchy of Finland]], [[Russian Empire]], the eighth child of Kalle (1835\u20131911) and Vilhelmiina Nieminen (1842\u20131918) in Ven\u00e4j\u00e4nniemi, Asikkala in 1878. He moved to [[Helsinki]] at the age of 21, where he worked as a stonemason.<ref name=\"sukutarina\">{{cite book | last1 = Halme | first1 = Seija | chapter = Sukutarina pitk\u00e4nmatkanjuoksuna: Ven\u00e4j\u00e4nniemi \u2013 Helsinki \u2013 New York | editor1-last= Roiko-Jokela | editor1-first = Heikki | editor2-last = Sironen | editor2-first = Esa | editor3-last = Viita | editor3-first = Ossi | title = Taidetta ja tehdasurheilua |series = Suomen urheiluhistoriallisen seuran vuosikirja | language = fi | volume = 2005 | location = Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 | publisher = Atena | publication-date = 2005 | pages = 39\u201347 | isbn = 951-796-414-5 | issn = 1237-3133 }}</ref>\n\nHe participated in his first race in 1903, when the longest ones held were [[Middle-distance running|middle-distance events]]. He became that year a member of the club [[Helsingin Koitto]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Vettenniemi | first1 = Erkki | year = 2006 | title = Joutavan juoksun j\u00e4ljill\u00e4. Kest\u00e4vyysjuoksun varhaisvaiheet Suomessa | trans-title = In Pursuit of Idle Running. The Early History of Long-Distance Running in Finland | series = Historiallisia tutkimuksia | language = fi | volume = 226 | location = Helsinki | publisher = Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura | page = 279 | isbn = 951-746-736-2 | issn = 0073-2559 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 1905 he won a [[10,000 metres|10,000 metre race]] with a Finnish record time 37:44.6.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Vettenniemi | first1 = Erkki | year = 2006 | title = Joutavan juoksun j\u00e4ljill\u00e4. Kest\u00e4vyysjuoksun varhaisvaiheet Suomessa | trans-title = In Pursuit of Idle Running. The Early History of Long-Distance Running in Finland | series = Historiallisia tutkimuksia | language = fi | volume = 226 | location = Helsinki | publisher = Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura | pages = 304\u2013305 | isbn = 951-746-736-2 | issn = 0073-2559 }}</ref> Soon he changed to the club [[Helsingin Reipas]]. On 16 September 1906, he won the first [[Marathon|marathon race]] held in Finland.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nIn September 1907, he had his first races abroad. In Stockholm, he tied the Finnish [[one hour run]] record with 16,759 meters, but at the time only races in Finland counted towards the record.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nIn 1908 he changed clubs to [[Helsingin Jyry]], where he also coached junior athletes. In May he won the Olympic selection marathon race and represented Finland at the [[Athletics at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's marathon|1908 Olympic marathon]], where he finished tenth with a time 3:09:50.8.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nHe ran his last race in Finland in August 1909, after which he emigrated to the United States to compete professionally.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nHis first professional race was in [[Philadelphia]] on 28 March 1910, when he won a two-man tag team relay marathon with [[William Kolehmainen]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Vettenniemi | first1 = Erkki | year = 2014 | title = Suomalaisen kest\u00e4vyysjuoksun historia | language = fi | location = Helsinki | publisher = Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura | page = 23 | isbn = 978-952-222-451-4 }}</ref>\n\nHis marathon personal best was 2:43:10, which he ran in [[Vailsburg, Newark]] in October 1912.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nAfter retirement, he coached long distance runners in [[Columbia University]]. He also earned a living as a masseur and a fox farmer.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\nHe made his last contact to his native Finland in the early 1920s, when he visited his sister's family in Asikkala. He died at the age of 68 in the United States in 1946. The news was not transmitted to anyone in Finland, where he was declared dead in absentia in 1971.<ref name=\"sukutarina\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nieminen, Kalle}}\n[[Category:Finnish male marathon runners]]\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Asikkala]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of Finland]]\n[[Category:Finnish emigrants to the United States (1809\u20131917)]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1908 Summer Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: long distance \u2192 long-distance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalle_Nieminen"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Metro Manila of the Philippines}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Metro Manila.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Confirmed cases in Metro Manila by local government unit (as of April 12){{refn|group=note|name=PHmapnote|Breakdown of confirmed cases is according to the [https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ COVID-19 Case Tracker] of the Department of Health. Take note that the map may not reflect all affected localities and is primarily based on the recorded place of residence of confirmed cases. Patients with confirmed COVID-19 infection may be referred to a health facility than their recorded place of residence.}}}}\n{{legend|#280b0b|500+ confirmed}}{{legend|#510000|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed}}{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed}}{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Metro Manila]]\n| first_case      = [[Manila]]\n| arrival_date    = January 30, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 302\n| deaths          = 219\n| confirmed_cases = 3,935\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{ubl|{{URL|http://www.covid19.gov.ph}}|{{URL|https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker}}}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Metro Manila]], Philippines on January 30, 2020, when the first case of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) was confirmed in the [[Manila|City of Manila]]. After a month of no new cases in the country, the first case of someone without travel history abroad was confirmed on March 5, a 62-year-old male who frequented a Muslim prayer hall in [[San Juan, Metro Manila]], raising suspicions that a community transmission of COVID-19 is already underway in the Philippines. The man's wife was confirmed to have contracted COVID-19 on March 7, which was also the first local transmission to be confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/san-juan-muslim-prayer-hall-coronavirus.html|title=San Juan prayer hall frequented by coronavirus patient temporarily closed|publisher=CNN Philippines|website=cnnphilippines.com|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/06/20/greenhills-mall-implements-precautionary-measures-vs-coronavirus|title=Greenhills Mall implements 'precautionary measures' vs coronavirus|work=ABS-CBN News|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> By March 13, Metro Manila was reported to be the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|worst affected region in the Philippines]] with 70 percent of all cases in the country at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/videos/2020/3/13/Most-cases-recorded-in-Metro-Manila.html |title=Most cases recorded in Metro Manila |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Bonquin, C. |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> A [[state of calamity]] and [[2020 Philippine community quarantines|community quarantine]] have been in place in the region since March 15.<ref name=\"philstar01\"/>\n\nAs of April 15, 2020, there have been 5,453 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the Philippines, 3,935 of which are residents of Metro Manila. There are 302 recoveries and 219 deaths in the region.<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Tracker |url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker |website=doh.gov.ph |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\nThe first confirmed case of COVID-19 in the Philippines was recorded in Metro Manila on January 30, 2020. It involved a 38-year-old Chinese woman from [[Wuhan]], the origin of the disease, who arrived in [[Manila]] after travelling to [[Cebu City]] and [[Dumaguete]] in central Philippines from [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"abs1\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus |title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Sabillo, K. |date=January 30, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Three days later, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Philippine Department of Health]] (DOH) confirmed that a second Chinese national tested positive for COVID-19, identified as the 44-year-old male companion of the first confirmed patient.<ref name=\"gma1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724482/philippines-confirms-2nd-novel-coronavirus-case-patient-dies/story/ |title=Philippines confirms 2nd novel coronavirus case, 1st death outside China |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Colcol, E. |date=February 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\nBoth patients received treatment at Manila's [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] with the latter being reported to have died from the disease on February 2, becoming the first known fatality outside [[China]].<ref name=\"gma1\"/> On March 6, the DOH reported the first case of local community transmission of the deadly virus, a 62-year-old Filipino man from suburban [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], just east of Metro Manila, with no prior travel history to affected countries.<ref name=\"cnn1\">{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/Philippines-coronavirus-local-case.html |title=Philippines records its first local case of coronavirus |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Tan, L. |date=March 6, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> He and his 59-year-old Filipino wife were initially admitted to the Cardinal Santos Medical Center in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] where they were diagnosed with the virus before being transferred to the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in [[Muntinlupa]] where they both died on March 11.<ref name=\"philstar2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000450/doh-first-local-transmission-wife-among-three-new-covid-19-deaths |title=First local COVID-19 transmission case, wife among 3 new deaths in Philippines |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, following the declaration of a public health emergency, Philippine President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] placed the entire capital region under community [[quarantine]] for 30 days starting March 15, 2020.<ref name=\"philstar1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000209/travel-and-manila-suspended-march-15-code-red-sublevel-2-raised-over-covid-19 |title=Travel to and from Manila suspended from March 15 as Code Red Sublevel 2 raised over COVID-19 |last=Luna |first=Franco |website=The Philippine Star |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Most areas in Metro Manila have also issued curfews to help limit the spread of the virus.<ref name=\"gma2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729731/manila-to-have-curfew-from-8-p-m-5-a-m-amid-covid-19-threat-says-mayor-isko/story/ |title=Several Metro Manila LGUs impose 8 p.m.-5 a.m. COVID-19 curfew |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Rita, J. |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, an [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine]] order was issued by the president covering Metro Manila and the entire island of [[Luzon]].<ref name=\"gazette1\"/>\n\nOn April 7, DOH secretary [[Francisco Duque]] reported that Metro Manila's COVID-19 cases continued to rise as 80 percent of the country's 3,764 confirmed cases were from the region. Duque also identified the cities with the most number of cases by the third week of the mass quarantine: Quezon City with 583, Manila with 221, [[Makati]] with 160, [[Para\u00f1aque]] with 155, and San Juan with 134 confirmed cases. The cities with the most reported deaths so far were identified as Quezon City with 34, Manila with 30, San Juan with 24, Pasig with 15, and [[Caloocan]] and Para\u00f1aque with 14 fatalities each.<ref name=\"gma0407\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/733067/philippines-covid-19-cases-concentrated-in-metro-manila-says-duque/story/ |title=Philippines' COVID-19 cases concentrated in Metro Manila, says Duque |publisher=[[GMA Network]] |author=Ornedo, J.M. |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, President Duterte announced that the Luzon-wide quarantine measures have been extended to April 30.<ref name=\"ecqex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/7/Luzon-lockdown-enhanced-community-quarantine-extension.html |title=Luzon-wide lockdown extended until April 30 to stop COVID-19 spread |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{Main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable floatright <!---mw-collapsible--->\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:90%; width:auto; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in NCR, Philippines<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\"/><br/><small>by city/municipality of residence<br/>Updated April 14, 2020 11:30 pm UTC+8</small> <small>''*based on cases validated by the local government''</small>\n! {{abbr|LGU|Local government unit}}\n! {{Hover title|Confirmed cases|Cases}}\n! Deaths\n! {{abbr|Recov.|Recoveries}}\n|-\n| [[Caloocan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 64\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 18\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 5\n|-\n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 78\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 7\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 11\n|-\n| [[Makati]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 199\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 21\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n|-\n| [[Malabon]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 28\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 6\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n|-\n| [[Mandaluyong]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 193\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 20\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 24\n|-\n| [[Manila]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 344\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 45\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 30\n|-\n| [[Marikina]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 68\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 18\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 6\n|-\n| [[Muntinlupa]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 98\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 15\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 14\n|-\n| [[Navotas]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 17\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 6\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n|-\n| [[Para\u00f1aque]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 184\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 17\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 9\n|-\n| [[Pasay]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 86\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 10\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 13\n|-\n| [[Pasig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 205\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 37\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 45\n|-\n| [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 15\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n|-\n| [[Quezon City]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 634\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 75\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 70\n|-\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 160\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 30\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 28\n|-\n| [[Taguig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 164\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 11\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 17\n|-\n| [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 46\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2,582\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 340\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 307\n|-\n|}\n* January 30 \u2013 The Philippines confirms its first case of coronavirus in Metro Manila and the entire country after a 38-year-old woman from [[Wuhan]] tested positive for COVID-19. She was hospitalized at [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in Manila.<ref name=\"abs1\"/>\n* February 2 \u2013 The first coronavirus-related death outside China was recorded in Manila. A 44-year-old Chinese man died while being treated at the San Lazaro Hospital.<ref name=\"gma1\"/>\n* March 6 \u2013 The first case of community transmission is reported by the DOH, a 62-year-old Filipino man from nearby [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], with no known history of travel abroad and who regularly visited a Muslim prayer hall in [[Greenhills (mixed-use development)|Greenhills]], San Juan.\n* March 7 \u2013 [[Taguig]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Modesto |first1=Catherine |title=Taguig-based firm says an employee tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/Deloitte-employee-coronavirus-positive.html?fbclid=IwAR2eajMCxa0Y6zVSNthbsokVZxfrigXjxrUufx5GA2PRVyMqC429Y77erv0 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 9 \n** [[Marikina]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Marikina coronavirus cases jump to 5 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1239830/marikina-govt-on-coronavirus-cases |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Pasig]],<ref>{{cite news |title=4 new confirmed coronavirus cases recorded in Metro Manila |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/9/Coronavirus-cases-Quezon-City-Philippines.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> and [[Quezon City]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=QC Mayor Joy Belmonte announces confirmed COVID-19 case in the city |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/728862/qc-mayor-joy-belmonte-announces-confirmed-covid-19-case-in-the-city/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> each record its first COVID-19 case.\n** The local governments of San Juan, Marikina, and [[Pasay]] order the suspension of classes for all levels amid the announcement of the first case of community transmission in the metropolis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/09/1999216/san-juan-marikina-pasay-suspend-classes-over-covid-19 |title=San Juan, Marikina, Pasay suspend classes over COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 10\n** President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] order the closure of all schools, colleges, and universities in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253912-walang-pasok-duterte-declares-class-suspensions-metro-manila-coronavirus-threat-march-10-14-2020 |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila March 10\u201314 over coronavirus threat |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority#Metro Manila Council|Metro Manila Council]], consisting of the Metro Manila mayors and headed by chairman [[Danilo Lim]], convene to discuss measures to prevent the spread of the virus as confirmed cases in the region climbed to 33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/03/10/20/metro-mayors-meet-on-local-lockdowns-after-coronavirus-cases-rise |title=Metro mayors meet on local lockdowns after coronavirus cases rise |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Cellona, J. |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 11 \n** [[Caloocan]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=One more COVID-19 patient in Tala hospital \u2013 Malapitan |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/11/one-more-covid-19-patient-in-tala-hospital-malapitan/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n** Manila Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] goes into self-quarantine and isolates himself in the [[Manila City Hall]] after arriving from an official trip to [[London]], U.K.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254164-isko-moreno-self-quarantines-manila-city-hall |title=Isko Moreno self-quarantines at Manila city hall |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Talabong, R. |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 12\n** Las Pi\u00f1as records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as records 1st COVID-19 case |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/12/20/las-pias-records-1st-covid-19-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n** President Duterte announces a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, placing the entire Metro Manila under community quarantine for thirty days beginning on March 15. The suspension of classes in all levels in Metro Manila is extended to April 12.<ref name=\"philstar01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000353/walang-pasok-duterte-suspends-metro-manila-classes-until-april-12 |title=Walang Pasok: Duterte suspends Metro Manila classes until April 12 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Patag, K.J. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** Incidents of [[panic buying]] are reported across the region, triggered by the president's partial lockdown order.<ref name=\"panic buying\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240902/look-panic-buying-amid-lockdown-fears-in-metro |title=LOOK: Panic-buying amid lockdown fears in Metro Manila |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13\n** The local chief executives of Caloocan, [[Malabon]], [[Navotas]], and [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]: [[Oscar Malapitan]], [[Antolin Oreta]], [[Toby Tiangco]], and [[Rex Gatchalian]], respectively, go into self-quarantine after learning they had come into contact with a confirmed coronavirus patient at a March 5 event in Caloocan's [[North Luzon Expressway]]\u2013Harbor Link.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240982/camanava-mayors-under-quarantine |title=Camanava mayors under quarantine |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Adonis, M. |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The DOH reports that four COVID-19 patients in the region had died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=CNN PH staff |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 14 \u2013 [[Mandaluyong]] records its first three COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\"Mandaluyong 1st case\">{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong declares state of calamity over spread of COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/mandaluyong-declares-state-of-calamity-over-spread-of-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 15\n** [[Muntinlupa]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa 1st case\">{{cite web |title=Muntinlupa City Declares State Of Calamity Due To COVID-19 Emergency |url=https://www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph/?p=18062 |publisher=City Government of Muntinlupa |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** A total of 56 checkpoints are set up in numerous points of entry to Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1242619/police-seal-metro-manila-to-fight-virus |title=Police seal Metro Manila to fight virus |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yamsuan, C.C. |author2=Agoncillo, J.A. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** Following a directive from the Metro Manila Council and the confirmation of COVID-19 cases, the city mayors of Makati, Manila, Pasig, and San Juan declare a [[State of emergency|state of calamity]].<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n* March 16 \u2013 President Duterte [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|imposes an enhanced community quarantine]] covering the entire [[Luzon]], including Metro Manila, suspending [[Transportation in the Philippines|mass public transportation]]; restricting land, air, and sea travel; imposing strict home quarantine; and closing most private establishments until April 13.<ref name=\"gazette1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=March 16, 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* March 17 \u2013 The Manila bourse becomes the first major market in the world to shut down over coronavirus fears. It suspends trading for two days following a [[2020 stock market crash|global stock market crash]] which saw the main [[Philippine Stock Exchange]] index plunge more than 30 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/philippines-shuts-financial-markets-after-virus-spurs-stock-rout |title=Philippines Becomes First Country to Shut Financial Markets Thanks to Virus |publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |author1=Tu, Lianting |author2=Sayson, Ian C. |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 19 \u2013 Valenzuela records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Valenzuela reports first COVID-19 case |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730416/valenzuela-reports-first-covid-19-case/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 23 \u2013 Malabon records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernardo |first1=Jaehwa |title=Malabon records first COVID-19 case |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/malabon-records-first-covid-19-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 24 \u2013 Several private hospitals in Metro Manila report operating at full-capacity due to the pandemic and urged patients to look for alternative hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247913/5-metro-hospitals-reach-full-capacity-for-covid-19-cases |title=5 Metro Manila hospitals reach full capacity for COVID-19 cases |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yamsuan, C.C. |author2=Yee, J. |date=March 25, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 28\n** Navotas records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Valenzuela |first1=Nikka |title=Navotas records first coronavirus case |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250197/navotas-records-first-coronavirus-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]], except [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport Terminal 1|Terminal 1]], closes following the suspension of domestic and international flights resulting from travel restriction impositions.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/28/2003833/airlines-mount-cargo-only-flights-transport-vital-goods |title=Airlines mount 'cargo-only' flights to transport vital goods |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Mercurio, R. |date=March 28, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] General Manager Jojo Garcia is confirmed as coronavirus positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/28/2003984/mmda-general-manager-positive-covid-19 |title=MMDA general manager positive for COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=March 28, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 31 \u2013 The [[Philippine National Police]] reports that 10,850 curfew violators have been apprehended across the region since the start of the enhanced community quarantines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1251886/pnp-records-more-than-70k-violators-of-quarantine-protocols |title=Over 70,000 violated Luzon-wide quarantine protocols \u2013 PNP |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 1\n** The local government of Manila reports its largest single-day increase in coronavirus infections so far with 41 new cases, bringing the city's total to 116.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/1/manila-records-largest-single-day-jump-coronavirus-.html |title=City of Manila records largest single-day jump in COVID-19\u00a0cases, total now at 116 |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** More than 800 Filipino repatriates from four virus-stricken cruise ships in the U.S. arrive at the Ninoy Aquino International Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256625-filipinos-united-states-cruise-ships-arrive-philippines-april-1-2020 |title=881 Filipinos from cruise ships in U.S. now back in PH |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 2\n**The Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases (IATF-EID) announced that Metro Manila remains the worst hit by the coronavirus crisis in the country after 1,511 cases were confirmed in the region, or more than 50 percent of the total confirmed cases in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/02/20/metro-manila-remains-ph-epicenter-of-coronavirus-crisis-galvez |title=Metro Manila remains PH epicenter of coronavirus crisis - Galvez |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Maru, D. |date=April 2, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 inter-agency taskforce spokesman [[Karlo Nograles]] announces the mandatory wearing of [[surgical mask|face mask]]s in public for residents in all regions under enhanced community quarantine in Luzon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256753-filipinos-luzon-required-wear-face-masks |title=Luzon residents now required to wear face masks when leaving homes |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=April 2, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 3 \u2013 The [[National Capital Region Police Office]] confirm its first COVID-19 casualty among its ranks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/03/news/latest-stories/2-policemen-succumb-to-virus/709280/ |title=2 policemen succumb to virus |publisher=[[The Manila Times]] |date=April 3, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 6\n**A ten-man medical team from China arrive in Manila to share their experience in prevention and control of the coronavirus disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/04/06/2005737/chinese-coronavirus-doctors-arrive-manila |title=Chinese coronavirus doctors arrive in Manila |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author1=Santos, R. |author2=Brago, P.L. |date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Human decontamination|Decontamination]] tents are installed in public hospitals and government offices across the region by the Metropolitan Manila Development Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/06/20/mmda-sets-up-decontamination-tents-in-public-hospitals-govt-offices |title=MMDA sets up decontamination tents in public hospitals, gov't offices |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 7\n**President Duterte approves an extension of the enhanced community quarantine in the region until April 30.<ref name=\"ecqex\"/>\n**The Health department launches a [[24/7 service|24/7]] coronavirus hotline for Metro Manila residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/7/Telemedicine-consultation-COVID.html |title=DOH launches telemedicine consultation for Metro Manila residents |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Embassy of the United States, Manila]] announce the cancellation of all scheduled visa appointments until May 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/08/20/us-embassy-in-manila-all-visa-interviews-until-may-4-cancelled |title=US embassy in Manila: All visa interviews until May 4 cancelled |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 8\n**The [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]] in [[Malate, Manila|Malate]] opens as a 116-bed COVID-19 emergency healthcare facility, with 108 more beds expected to be completed by April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/294438/rizal-memorial-stadium-ready-to-accept-initial-116-covid-19-patients |title=Rizal Memorial Stadium ready to accept initial 116 COVID-19 patients |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Abadilla, D.D. |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[World Health Organization]] Western Pacific Regional Office in Manila express its approval of the quarantine measures as it claims it was able to prevent a large-scale community outbreak of the virus in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/8/WHO-PH-lockdown-prevent-large-scale-community-quarantine.html |title=Lockdown saves PH from large-scale community outbreak, WHO says |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Ferreras, V. |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 11\n**Mass testing begins in [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela City]].<ref name=\"Valenzuela Mass Testing\" />\n*April 14\n**Localized mass testing in the [[Manila|City of Manila]] and [[Quezon City]] starts.<ref name=\"MNLQC Mass Testing\" />\n<!-- Please write entries in PRESENT tense. -->\n\n== Statistics ==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=900\n|colors= #FF6347, #FFC000, #87CEEB, #000000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x= Mar 6, Mar 8, Mar 9, Mar 10, Mar 11, Mar 12, Mar 13, Mar 14, Mar 15, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 18, Mar 19, Mar 20, Mar 21, Mar 22, Mar 23, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 31, Apr 1, Apr 2, Apr 3, Apr 4, Apr 5, Apr 6, Apr 7, Apr 8, Apr 9, Apr 10, Apr 11, Apr 12, Apr 13, Apr 14, Apr 15, Apr 16\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1= 1, 5, 17, 24, 37, 39, 46, 82, 104, 106, 144, 155, 168, 181, 238, 295, 360, 431, 494, 540, 617, 809, 1070, 1136, 1542, 1702, 1939, 2219, 2271, 2383, 2697, 2756, 2829, 2988, 3058, 3224, 3335, 3510, 3621, 3785, 3935\n|y1Title=Confirmed \n|y2= , , , 3, 10, 10, 15, 36, 50, 51, 75, 82, 91, 100, 140, 180, 233, 293, 344, 381, 446, 618, 857, 914, 1287, 1438, 1665, 1935, 1980, 2093, 2394, 2452, 2524, 2679, 2749, 2913, 3024, 3199, 3271, 3375, 3414\n|y2Title=Active \n|y3= 1, 4, 14, 17, 21, 23, 24, 38, 43, 44, 54, 56, 57, 60, 71, 79, 82, 90, 95, 96, 97, 104, 113, 114, 125, 127, 130, 130, 131, 131, 132, 132, 132, 132, 132, 132, 132, 132, 154, 203, 302\n|y3Title=Recoveries\n|y4= , 1, 3, 4, 6, 6, 7, 8, 11, 11, 15, 17, 20, 21, 27, 36, 45, 48, 55, 63, 74, 87, 100, 108,