{"title_page": "Jarnail Singh (referee)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Jarnail Singh\n| image =  Jarnail Singh.jpg\n| caption = Jarnail Singh\n| fullname = Jarnail Singh\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|02|05}}\n| birth_place = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| otheroccupation = [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] [[Wage labour|worker]] <br/> [[Taxi Driver]] <br/> Corner shop owner <br/> Kirpan seller\n| years1  = ? \u20132004\n| league1 = [[Conference South]]\n| role1   = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years2  = 1999\u20132004\n| league2 = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n| role2   = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Asst. referee]]\n| years3  = 2004\u20132010\n| league3 = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n| role3   = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n}}\n\n'''Jarnail Singh''' (born 5 February 1962<ref name=\"flprofile\">[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0,,10794~628215,00.html Profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080417072957/http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10794~628215%2C00.html |date=17 April 2008 }}: [[The Football League]] official website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008</ref> in [[India]])<ref name=\"flinterview\">[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Interviews/0,,10794~701925,00.html Other biographical detail]: from an interview at the Football League official website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008</ref> is a retired [[England|English]] [[association football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]] of [[India]]n descent who officiated in [[the Football League]]. He moved to [[Wolverhampton]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], at a young age, and now lives in [[Hounslow]], [[Greater London]].<ref>[http://www.soccerfactsuk.co.uk/reffixtures.php?refid=102 Place of residence confirmation] ([[Hounslow]]): ''SoccerFactsUK.co.uk'' website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008</ref> He has a full-time occupation in the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] in [[London]].<ref name=\"flinterview\" /> Singh is also an ambassador for the [[Football Association]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.asianfootballnetwork.org.uk/case-studies/case-study.php?s=refereeing-jarnail-singh&cat=asian-football-coaches-referees | title=Case Studies - Jarnail Singh | publisher=www.asianfootballnetwork.ork.uk | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> He was the first [[Sikh]] to be an English Football referee.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Sikhs-in-other-sports-countries-never-told-to-remove-turbans/articleshow/38939493.cms | title=Sikhs in other sports & countries never told to remove turbans | publisher=Times of India | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSingh took up refereeing in 1985,<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> after taking his exam in order to improve his frequent outings as [[Official (sports)#Football (association)|club linesman]] for the youth team he managed.<ref name=\"flinterview\" /> He progressed through lower leagues in the [[Wolverhampton]] area and then into the [[Conference South]] regionally,<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/refs2.sd?refid=810&seasonid=133 Conference South referee], until 2004 season: [[soccerbase]].com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref> before being appointed as a [[The Football League|Football League]] [[Assistant referee (association football)|assistant referee]] in 1999. Whilst still a Conference referee, he was put in charge of an [[FA Vase]] [[semi-final]] first leg tie, between [[Oadby Town F.C.|Oadby Town]] and [[Brigg Town F.C.|Brigg Town]] on 22 March 2003,<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=385317 FA Vase semi-final first leg], 2003: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref> and, shortly before his elevation to Football League referee for the [[2004-05 in English football|2004-05]] season,<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> he was appointed to the middle for the [[Conference National#Past Conference winners|Football Conference Playoff]] semi-final first leg between [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] and [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] on 29 April 2004.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=421701 Football Conference Playoff semi-final first leg], 2004: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref>\n\nHis first match after his promotion was the [[Football League Two]] encounter between [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] and [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] at the [[Memorial Stadium (Bristol)|Memorial Stadium]] on 10 August 2004, in which he [[Misconduct (football)#Sending-off offences (red card)|sent off]] [[Colin Woodthorpe]] of Bury in the 65th minute.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=427811 First ever Football League match as referee], Bristol Rovers v. Bury, 2004: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref>\n\nHis final match before retirement was on 1 May 2010, refereeing a [[Football League One|League One]] game between [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] versus [[Oldham Athletic F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] at [[Huish Park]] in [[Yeovil]]. Before the match he was unusually signing autographs and having photos taken with fans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yeovilexpress.co.uk/sport/8133322.Yeovil_Town_thank_referee_Jarnail_Singh/ |title=Yeovil Town thank referee Jarnail Singh |publisher=Yeovil Express |date=3 May 2010 |accessdate=9 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nHe has refereed at international level taking charge of a friendly game between [[China national football team|China]] and [[United Arab Emirates national football team|UAE]] in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/jarnail-singh/3/1/freundschaft-2011/ | title=Jarnail Singh | publisher=www.worldfootball.net | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a role model, [[The Football Association|The FA]] acknowledged the importance of his visibility.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmcumeds/89/89we03.htm |title=Culture, Media and Sport Committee - Racism in Football. Written evidence submitted by The Football Association (The FA) |publisher=https://publications.parliament.uk |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> In 2012, he received a Lifetime Achievement Award at the first Asian Football Awards supported by the Football Association and the anti-discrimination organisation, [[Kick It Out (organisation)|Kick It Out]].<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.thefa.com/news/governance/equality/2012/aug/asian-football-awards-2012 | title=Asian stars rewarded at Wembley | publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=5 August 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSingh is employed by the Metropolitan Police as a [[Police Community Support Officer]] in London, and is married with two children, Sunny and Bhupsy Gill, who are now also qualified referees.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.refworld.com/referee/167/1 |title=refworld.com |access-date=2 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529032249/http://www.refworld.com/referee/167/1 |archive-date=29 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase referee|810}}\n*{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529032249/http://www.refworld.com/referee/167/1 |title=National Group Profile - Jarnail Singh at refworld.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Jarnail}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:People from Hounslow]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Indian football referees]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Jarnail Singh\n| image =  Jarnail Singh.jpg\n| caption = Jarnail Singh\n| fullname = Jarnail Singh\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|02|05}}\n| birth_place = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| otheroccupation = [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] [[Wage labour|worker]] | [[Taxi Driver]] | Corner shop owner | Kirpan seller\n| years1  = ? \u20132004\n| league1 = [[Conference South]]\n| role1   = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years2  = 1999\u20132004\n| league2 = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n| role2   = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Asst. referee]]\n| years3  = 2004\u20132010\n| league3 = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n| role3   = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n}}\n\n'''Jarnail Singh''' (born 5 February 1962<ref name=\"flprofile\">[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0,,10794~628215,00.html Profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080417072957/http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10794~628215%2C00.html |date=17 April 2008 }}: [[The Football League]] official website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008</ref> in [[India]])<ref name=\"flinterview\">[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Interviews/0,,10794~701925,00.html Other biographical detail]: from an interview at the Football League official website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008</ref> is a retired [[England|English]] [[association football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]] of [[India]]n descent who officiated in [[the Football League]]. He moved to [[Wolverhampton]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], at a young age, and now lives in [[Hounslow]], [[Greater London]].<ref>[http://www.soccerfactsuk.co.uk/reffixtures.php?refid=102 Place of residence confirmation] ([[Hounslow]]): ''SoccerFactsUK.co.uk'' website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008</ref> He has a full-time occupation in the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] in [[London]].<ref name=\"flinterview\" /> Singh is also an ambassador for the [[Football Association]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.asianfootballnetwork.org.uk/case-studies/case-study.php?s=refereeing-jarnail-singh&cat=asian-football-coaches-referees | title=Case Studies - Jarnail Singh | publisher=www.asianfootballnetwork.ork.uk | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> He was the first [[Sikh]] to be an English Football referee.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Sikhs-in-other-sports-countries-never-told-to-remove-turbans/articleshow/38939493.cms | title=Sikhs in other sports & countries never told to remove turbans | publisher=Times of India | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSingh took up refereeing in 1985,<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> after taking his exam in order to improve his frequent outings as [[Official (sports)#Football (association)|club linesman]] for the youth team he managed.<ref name=\"flinterview\" /> He progressed through lower leagues in the [[Wolverhampton]] area and then into the [[Conference South]] regionally,<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/refs2.sd?refid=810&seasonid=133 Conference South referee], until 2004 season: [[soccerbase]].com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref> before being appointed as a [[The Football League|Football League]] [[Assistant referee (association football)|assistant referee]] in 1999. Whilst still a Conference referee, he was put in charge of an [[FA Vase]] [[semi-final]] first leg tie, between [[Oadby Town F.C.|Oadby Town]] and [[Brigg Town F.C.|Brigg Town]] on 22 March 2003,<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=385317 FA Vase semi-final first leg], 2003: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref> and, shortly before his elevation to Football League referee for the [[2004-05 in English football|2004-05]] season,<ref name=\"flprofile\" /> he was appointed to the middle for the [[Conference National#Past Conference winners|Football Conference Playoff]] semi-final first leg between [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] and [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] on 29 April 2004.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=421701 Football Conference Playoff semi-final first leg], 2004: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref>\n\nHis first match after his promotion was the [[Football League Two]] encounter between [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] and [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] at the [[Memorial Stadium (Bristol)|Memorial Stadium]] on 10 August 2004, in which he [[Misconduct (football)#Sending-off offences (red card)|sent off]] [[Colin Woodthorpe]] of Bury in the 65th minute.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=427811 First ever Football League match as referee], Bristol Rovers v. Bury, 2004: soccerbase.com website. Retrieved on 24 March 2008.</ref>\n\nHis final match before retirement was on 1 May 2010, refereeing a [[Football League One|League One]] game between [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] versus [[Oldham Athletic F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] at [[Huish Park]] in [[Yeovil]]. Before the match he was unusually signing autographs and having photos taken with fans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yeovilexpress.co.uk/sport/8133322.Yeovil_Town_thank_referee_Jarnail_Singh/ |title=Yeovil Town thank referee Jarnail Singh |publisher=Yeovil Express |date=3 May 2010 |accessdate=9 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nHe has refereed at international level taking charge of a friendly game between [[China national football team|China]] and [[United Arab Emirates national football team|UAE]] in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/jarnail-singh/3/1/freundschaft-2011/ | title=Jarnail Singh | publisher=www.worldfootball.net | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a role model, [[The Football Association|The FA]] acknowledged the importance of his visibility.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmcumeds/89/89we03.htm |title=Culture, Media and Sport Committee - Racism in Football. Written evidence submitted by The Football Association (The FA) |publisher=https://publications.parliament.uk |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> In 2012, he received a Lifetime Achievement Award at the first Asian Football Awards supported by the Football Association and the anti-discrimination organisation, [[Kick It Out (organisation)|Kick It Out]].<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.thefa.com/news/governance/equality/2012/aug/asian-football-awards-2012 | title=Asian stars rewarded at Wembley | publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=5 August 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSingh is employed by the Metropolitan Police as a [[Police Community Support Officer]] in London, and is married with two children, Sunny and Bhupsy Gill, who are now also qualified referees.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.refworld.com/referee/167/1 |title=refworld.com |access-date=2 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529032249/http://www.refworld.com/referee/167/1 |archive-date=29 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soccerbase.com/refs2.sd?refid=810 Jarnail Singh Referee Statistics] at [[soccerbase]].com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100529032249/http://www.refworld.com/referee/167/1 National Group Profile - Jarnail Singh] at refworld.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Jarnail}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:People from Hounslow]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Indian football referees]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update infobox and links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jarnail_Singh_(referee)"}
{"title_page": "Yoshmut", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty|name=Yoshmut|death_date={{Death date|1271|7|18}}|house=[[Borjigin]]|succession=Viceroy of [[Arran (Caucasus)|Arran]] and [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]]|spouse=|issue=|predecessor=|successor=|birth_date=after 1234|title=|death_place=|birth_place=[[Mongolia]]|burial_place=|reign=1265 - 1271|father=[[Hulagu]]|mother=Nogachin Aghachi|image=Bataille_de_Miyafarkin_(1259).jpeg|caption=Battle of Mayyafaraqin (1259) headed by Yoshmut <br> Shams al-D\u00een K\u00e2sh\u00e2n\u00ee, [[15th century]]|reign-type=}}\n\n'''Yoshmut''' ({{Lang-fa|\u064a\u0648\u0634\u0645\u0648\u062a}}) was [[Ilkhanate]] prince and one of eldest sons of [[Hulagu Khan|Hulagu]]. According to Dai Matsui<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u767d (Dai)|first=\u7389\u51ac (Matsui)|last2=\u677e\u4e95 (Yudong)|first2=\u592a (Bai)|date=2016-10-31|title=\u30d5\u30d5\u30db\u30c8\u767d\u5854\u306e\u30a6\u30a4\u30b0\u30eb\u8a9e\u984c\u8a18\u9298\u6587|trans-title=Old Uigjur Inscriptions of the White Pagoda, Hohhot|url=http://hdl.handle.net/11094/58627|journal=\u5185\u9678\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u8a00\u8a9e\u306e\u7814\u7a76|volume=31|pages=29\u201377|issn=13415670|via=}}</ref> and Daniel King<ref>{{Cite book|last=King|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e-GEDwAAQBAJ|title=The Syriac World|date=2018-12-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-48211-6|language=en}}</ref>, his name was of Christian [[Old Uyghur language|Uyghur]] origin and ultimately derived from [[Sogdian language|Sogdian]] word \"''\u02bfyw\u0161mbt''\" (cognate with {{Lang-fa|\u062f\u0648\u0634\u0646\u0628\u0647|translit=Yekshanbeh|lit=Monday}}).\n\n== Life ==\nHe was born to [[Hulagu Khan|Hulagu]] and his concubine Nogachin Aghachi, a lady of Chinese of Khitan origin from camp of Qutui Khatun in Mongolia. One of the three eldest sons of Hulagu, he accompanied his father with [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]] to Iran from 1253.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hope|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=weMoDQAAQBAJ|title=Power, Politics, and Tradition in the Mongol Empire and the \u012alkh\u0101nate of Iran|date=2016-09-29|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-108108-8|location=|pages=113-114|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Under Hulagu ==\nHis first assignment was subjugation of [[Mayyafaraqin]] with Sontai Noyan and Ilga Noyan of [[Jalairs]] in 1259 after Hulagu's conquest of [[Diyar Bakr]]. However [[Ayyubid dynasty|Ayyubid]] [[malik]] of the city al-Kamil Muhammad resisted Yoshmut for a while, despite reinforcements from [[Mosul]] sent by [[Badr al-Din Lu'lu']]. This angered Hulagu who recalled Yoshmut after 10 months.<ref name=\":0\" /> City held until April 1260<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jackson|first=Peter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uiOMDgAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols and the Islamic World: From Conquest to Conversion|date=2017-04-04|publisher=Yale University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-300-22728-4|location=|pages=130|language=en}}</ref> when al-Kamil finally surrendered to Mongol army. Turned over to Hulagu's camp in [[Tell Bashir]], al-Kamil was forced to eat his own flesh.<ref>{{Cite book|last=M\u012br|first=Ghiy\u0101s\u0332 al-D\u012bn ibn Hum\u0101m al-D\u012bn Khv\u0101nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dZIPAQAAMAAJ|title=Habib\u00fc's-siyer: Mo\u011fol ve T\u00fcrk h\u00e2kimiyeti|date=1994|publisher=Department of Near Eastern Languages and Civilizations, Harvard University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=56|language=en}}</ref> After Mayyafaraqin, Yoshmut was sent to [[Mardin]], which was ruled by [[Artuqids|Artuqid]] bey Al-Sa'id Najm al-Din Ghazi I. Mardin resisted the siege for over 8 months until death of Najm al-Din. New bey Qara Arslan surrendered castle to Yoshmut and accepted Ilkhanate overlordship. Nevertheless, angry Hulagu reprimanded Yoshmut for his inability and banned him from the army that was going to battle [[Golden Horde]] in 1262. Despite all, before his death in 1265, Hulagu appointed his sons [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]] to viceroyalty of [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]] and Yoshmut to [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]], [[Arran (Caucasus)|Arran]], [[Shirvan]] and in general march of [[Derbent]]. Yoshmut arrived at Derbent on 16 February 1265, a week after his father's death.\n\n== Under Abaqa ==\nHearing news of his father's death, Yoshmut rushed to capital, unsuccessfully campaigning for [[kurultai]] but losing hope returning to Derbent after 2 days. In turn, [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]] reaffirmed his position in Derbent on 19 June 1265, on day of his coronation. After Abaqa's election, [[Ilkhanate]] faced another invasion by [[Golden Horde]]. Yoshmut fought with Golden Horde commander [[Nogai Khan|Nogai]] on banks of [[Agsu District|Aqsu]] river in [[Shirvan]] on 19-20 July 1265 and managed to shoot him in the eye after a fierce battle, forcing him to retreat. Abaqa pursued Nogai's army across the Kur, hoping to wipe it out, but Abaqa was forced to withdraw when [[Berke]] arrived with reinforcements.<ref>Henry Hoyle Howorth. \"History of the Mongols.\" 1876. Page 1012.</ref>\n\nYoshmut participated in his brother's war with 10.000 soldiers<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Cosmo|first=Nicola Di|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UaWODwAAQBAJ|title=Warfare in Inner Asian History (500-1800)|date=2001-12-21|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-39178-9|location=|pages=191-196|language=en}}</ref> in 1270 against Chagatai khan [[Ghiyas-ud-din Baraq|Baraq]], who was threatening Ilkhanate borders. While Abaqa was dealing with [[Teguder (Chagatai prince)|Teg\u00fcder]] in west, Yoshmut battled with Baraq, often faced with defeats. After Abaqa's arrival on vicinity of [[Herat]], he was given command of left flank with [[Arghun Aqa]], [[Atabegs of Yazd|Atabeg Yusufshah of Yazd]], [[Muzaffar al-Din Hajjaj]], Sontai Noyan, Buriltai Noyan, Shiktur Noyan and Abdallah Aqa commanding under him.<ref name=\":1\" />Battle was won after three assaults on 22 July 1270 and resulted with Baraq's flee.\n\n== Death and legacy ==\nYoshmut died on 18 July 1271<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cab\u012bb|first=Rash\u012bd al-D\u012bn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6ZmAAAAMAAJ|title=Compendium of Chronicles|date=1999|publisher=Harvard University, Department of Near Eastern Languages and Civilizations|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=535|language=en|translator-last=Thackston|translator-first=Wheeler McIntosh}}</ref>. He was known for his hot temper and unpopularity among military. One of his descendants - Ilyas - became a figurehead Ilkhan with the regnal name [[Suleiman Khan]]. \n\n== Family ==\nHe had at least four sons:\n\n# Qara Noqai \u2014 took part in [[Nawr\u016bz (Mongol emir)|Nawruz]]'s revolt, executed by [[Arghun]] on 7 Oct 1289 with his children in [[Damghan]].\n# Sogai \u2014 executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296 for Sulamish's revolt in [[Anatolia]].\n## Yusufshah\n### [[Suleiman Khan|Ilyas]]\n# Janbu \u2014 died on 31 December 1291, on Jaghatu plains\n\nAnother son of Yoshmut was attested in Turkish sources named Jumudar ({{Lang-ota|\u062c\u0645\u0648\u062f|translit=Cumud\u00e2r}}).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Yasar|first=H\u00fcseyin H\u00fcsameddin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FOBAAQAAMAAJ|title=Amasya tarihi|date=1910|publisher=Matbaa-i \u0130slamiyesi|year=|isbn=|volume=2|location=[[Istanbul]]|pages=437|language=ar}}</ref> His mummified body was found in Amasya and his death was dated to 1296, [[Ghazan]]'s reign.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Efe|first=Zehra|date=April 2014|title=The History and Present Status of Mummies in Turkish Museums and Shrines|url=https://docplayer.biz.tr/29189217-Turkiye-muze-ve-turbelerindeki-mumyalarin-tarihi-ve-bugunku-durumlari.html|journal=SDU Faculty of Arts and Sciences Journal of Social Sciences|volume=|pages=279-292|archive-url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:445wfC9BlvYJ:dergipark.org.tr/download/issue-file/1146|archive-date=April 2020|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=\u0410\u043d\u0445\u0431\u0430\u044f\u0440|first=\u0414.|title=\u041c\u043e\u043d\u0433\u043e\u043b\u044b\u043d \u0418\u043b \u0445\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0443\u043b\u0441\u044b\u043d \u0442\u04af\u04af\u0445 \u0441\u043e\u0451\u043b\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0445\u043e\u043b\u0431\u043e\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a \u0434\u0430\u0445\u044c \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043c \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440, \u0434\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0433\u0430\u043b\u0442 \u0437\u04af\u0439\u043b\u0441|last2=\u0411\u0430\u0442\u0445\u0438\u0448\u0438\u0433|first2=\u0411.|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=|location=[[Ankara]]|pages=|trans-title=Some places and monuments in Turkey related to the history and culture of the Mongolian Ilkhanate}}</ref> It is being displayed in [[Amasya Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2016/11/11/mummies-of-anatolia-still-a-matter-of-interest|title=Mummies of Anatolia still a matter of interest|last=Ekinci|first=Ekrem Bu\u011fra|date=2016-11-11|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Ilkhanate]]\n[[Category:1271 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty|name=Yoshmut|death_date={{Death date|1271|7|18}}|house=[[Borjigin]]|succession=Viceroy of [[Arran (Caucasus)|Arran]] and [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]]|spouse=|issue=|predecessor=|successor=|birth_date=after 1234|title=|death_place=|birth_place=[[Mongolia]]|burial_place=|reign=1265 - 1271|father=[[Hulagu]]|mother=Nogachin Aghachi|image=Bataille_de_Miyafarkin_(1259).jpeg|caption=Battle of Mayyafaraqin (1259) headed by Yoshmut <br> Shams al-D\u00een K\u00e2sh\u00e2n\u00ee, [[15th century]]|reign-type=}}\n\n'''Yoshmut''' ({{Lang-fa|\u064a\u0648\u0634\u0645\u0648\u062a}}) was [[Ilkhanate]] prince and one of eldest sons of [[Hulagu Khan|Hulagu]]. According to Dai Matsui<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u767d (Dai)|first=\u7389\u51ac (Matsui)|last2=\u677e\u4e95 (Yudong)|first2=\u592a (Bai)|date=2016-10-31|title=\u30d5\u30d5\u30db\u30c8\u767d\u5854\u306e\u30a6\u30a4\u30b0\u30eb\u8a9e\u984c\u8a18\u9298\u6587|trans-title=Old Uigjur Inscriptions of the White Pagoda, Hohhot|url=http://hdl.handle.net/11094/58627|journal=\u5185\u9678\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u8a00\u8a9e\u306e\u7814\u7a76|volume=31|pages=29\u201377|issn=13415670|via=}}</ref> and Daniel King<ref>{{Cite book|last=King|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e-GEDwAAQBAJ|title=The Syriac World|date=2018-12-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-48211-6|language=en}}</ref>, his name was of Christian [[Old Uyghur language|Uyghur]] origin and ultimately derived from [[Sogdian language|Sogdian]] word \"''\u02bfyw\u0161mbt''\" (cognate with {{Lang-fa|\u062f\u0648\u0634\u0646\u0628\u0647|translit=Yekshanbeh|lit=Monday}}).\n\n== Life ==\nHe was born to [[Hulagu Khan|Hulagu]] and his concubine Nogachin Aghachi, a lady of Chinese of Khitan origin from camp of Qutui Khatun in Mongolia. One of the three eldest sons of Hulagu, he accompanied his father with [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]] to Iran from 1253.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hope|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=weMoDQAAQBAJ|title=Power, Politics, and Tradition in the Mongol Empire and the \u012alkh\u0101nate of Iran|date=2016-09-29|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-108108-8|location=|pages=113-114|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Under Hulagu ==\nHis first assignment was subjugation of [[Mayyafaraqin]] with Sontai Noyan and Ilga Noyan of [[Jalairs]] in 1259 after Hulagu's conquest of [[Diyar Bakr]]. However [[Ayyubid dynasty|Ayyubid]] [[malik]] of the city al-Kamil Muhammad resisted Yoshmut for a while, despite reinforcements from [[Mosul]] sent by [[Badr al-Din Lu'lu']]. This angered Hulagu who recalled Yoshmut after 10 months.<ref name=\":0\" /> City held until April 1260<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jackson|first=Peter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uiOMDgAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols and the Islamic World: From Conquest to Conversion|date=2017-04-04|publisher=Yale University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-300-22728-4|location=|pages=130|language=en}}</ref> when al-Kamil finally surrendered to Mongol army. Turned over to Hulagu's camp in [[Tell Bashir]], al-Kamil was forced to eat his own flesh.<ref>{{Cite book|last=M\u012br|first=Ghiy\u0101s\u0332 al-D\u012bn ibn Hum\u0101m al-D\u012bn Khv\u0101nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dZIPAQAAMAAJ|title=Habib\u00fc's-siyer: Mo\u011fol ve T\u00fcrk h\u00e2kimiyeti|date=1994|publisher=Department of Near Eastern Languages and Civilizations, Harvard University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=56|language=en}}</ref> After Mayyafaraqin, Yoshmut was sent to [[Mardin]], which was ruled by [[Artuqids|Artuqid]] bey Al-Sa'id Najm al-Din Ghazi I. Mardin resisted the siege for over 8 months until death of Najm al-Din. New bey Qara Arslan surrendered castle to Yoshmut and accepted Ilkhanate overlordship. Nevertheless, angry Hulagu reprimanded Yoshmut for his inability and banned him from the army that was going to battle [[Golden Horde]] in 1262. Nevertheless, before his death in 1265, Hulagu appointed his sons [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]] to viceroyalty of [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]] and Yoshmut to [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]], [[Arran (Caucasus)|Arran]], [[Shirvan]] and in general march of [[Derbent]]. Yoshmut arrived at Derbent on 16 February 1265, a week after his father's death.\n\n== Under Abaqa ==\nHearing news of his father's death, Yoshmut rushed to capital, unsuccessfully campaigning for [[kurultai]] but losing hope returning to Derbent after 2 days. In turn, [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]] reaffirmed his position in Derbent on 19 June 1265, on day of his coronation. After Abaqa's election, [[Ilkhanate]] faced another invasion by [[Golden Horde]]. Yoshmut fought with Golden Horde commander [[Nogai Khan|Nogai]] on banks of [[Agsu District|Aqsu]] river in [[Shirvan]] on 19-20 July 1265 and managed to shoot him in the eye after a fierce battle, forcing him to retreat. Abaqa pursued Nogai's army across the Kur, hoping to wipe it out, but Abaqa was forced to withdraw when [[Berke]] arrived with reinforcements.<ref>Henry Hoyle Howorth. \"History of the Mongols.\" 1876. Page 1012.</ref>\n\nYoshmut participated in his brother's war with 10.000 soldiers<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Cosmo|first=Nicola Di|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UaWODwAAQBAJ|title=Warfare in Inner Asian History (500-1800)|date=2001-12-21|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-39178-9|location=|pages=191-196|language=en}}</ref> in 1270 against Chagatai khan [[Ghiyas-ud-din Baraq|Baraq]], who was threatening Ilkhanate borders. While Abaqa was dealing with [[Teguder (Chagatai prince)|Teg\u00fcder]] in west, Yoshmut battled with Baraq, often faced with defeats. After Abaqa's arrival on vicinity of [[Herat]], he was given command of left flank with [[Arghun Aqa]], [[Atabegs of Yazd|Atabeg Yusufshah of Yazd]], [[Muzaffar al-Din Hajjaj]], Sontai Noyan, Buriltai Noyan, Shiktur Noyan and Abdallah Aqa commanding under him.<ref name=\":1\" />Battle was won after three assaults on 22 July 1270 and resulted with Baraq's flee.\n\n== Death and legacy ==\nYoshmut died on 18 July 1271<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cab\u012bb|first=Rash\u012bd al-D\u012bn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6ZmAAAAMAAJ|title=Compendium of Chronicles|date=1999|publisher=Harvard University, Department of Near Eastern Languages and Civilizations|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=535|language=en|translator-last=Thackston|translator-first=Wheeler McIntosh}}</ref>. He was known for his hot temper and unpopularity among military. One of his descendants - Ilyas - became a figurehead Ilkhan with the regnal name [[Suleiman Khan]]. \n\n== Family ==\nHe had at least four sons:\n\n# Qara Noqai \u2014 took part in [[Nawr\u016bz (Mongol emir)|Nawruz]]'s revolt, executed by [[Arghun]] on 7 Oct 1289 with his children in [[Damghan]].\n# Sogai \u2014 executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296 for Sulamish's revolt in [[Anatolia]].\n## Yusufshah\n### [[Suleiman Khan|Ilyas]]\n# Janbu \u2014 died on 31 December 1291, on Jaghatu plains\n\nAnother son of Yoshmut was attested in Turkish sources named Jumudar ({{Lang-ota|\u062c\u0645\u0648\u062f|translit=Cumud\u00e2r}}).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Yasar|first=H\u00fcseyin H\u00fcsameddin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FOBAAQAAMAAJ|title=Amasya tarihi|date=1910|publisher=Matbaa-i \u0130slamiyesi|year=|isbn=|volume=2|location=[[Istanbul]]|pages=437|language=ar}}</ref> His mummified body was found in Amasya and his death was dated to 1296, [[Ghazan]]'s reign.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Efe|first=Zehra|date=April 2014|title=The History and Present Status of Mummies in Turkish Museums and Shrines|url=https://docplayer.biz.tr/29189217-Turkiye-muze-ve-turbelerindeki-mumyalarin-tarihi-ve-bugunku-durumlari.html|journal=SDU Faculty of Arts and Sciences Journal of Social Sciences|volume=|pages=279-292|archive-url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:445wfC9BlvYJ:dergipark.org.tr/download/issue-file/1146|archive-date=April 2020|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=\u0410\u043d\u0445\u0431\u0430\u044f\u0440|first=\u0414.|title=\u041c\u043e\u043d\u0433\u043e\u043b\u044b\u043d \u0418\u043b \u0445\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0443\u043b\u0441\u044b\u043d \u0442\u04af\u04af\u0445 \u0441\u043e\u0451\u043b\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0445\u043e\u043b\u0431\u043e\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a \u0434\u0430\u0445\u044c \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043c \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440, \u0434\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0433\u0430\u043b\u0442 \u0437\u04af\u0439\u043b\u0441|last2=\u0411\u0430\u0442\u0445\u0438\u0448\u0438\u0433|first2=\u0411.|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=|location=[[Ankara]]|pages=|trans-title=Some places and monuments in Turkey related to the history and culture of the Mongolian Ilkhanate}}</ref> It is being displayed in [[Amasya Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2016/11/11/mummies-of-anatolia-still-a-matter-of-interest|title=Mummies of Anatolia still a matter of interest|last=Ekinci|fir