{"title_page": "Algebraic specification", "text_new": "'''Algebraic specification''',<ref>{{cite book|title=Algebraic Specification|first=H.|last= Ehrig|author2=B. Mahr|publisher=Academic Press|year=1989|isbn=0-201-41635-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Algebraic Specification|first=J.A.|last=Bergstra|author2=J. Heering |author3=J. Klint |publisher=Springer-Verlag|year=1985|series=EATCS Monographs on Theoretical Computer Science|volume=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Algebraic Specification|first=M.|last=[[Martin Wirsing|Wirsing]]|series=Handbook of Theoretical Computer Science|volume=B|editor=[[Jan van Leeuwen]]|year=1990|publisher=Elsevier|pages=675\u2013788}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Foundations of Algebraic Specification and Formal Software Development|first=Donald|last=Sannella|author2=Andrzej Tarlecki|publisher=Springer-Verlag|year=2012|series=EATCS Monographs on Theoretical Computer Science|isbn=978-3-642-17335-6}}</ref> is a software engineering technique for [[formal specification|formally specifying]] system behavior.  Algebraic specification seeks to systematically develop more efficient programs by:\n\n# formally defining [[data type|types of data]], and mathematical operations on those data types\n# abstracting implementation details, such as the size of representations (in memory) and the efficiency of obtaining outcome of computations\n# formalizing the computations and operations on data types\n# allowing for automation by formally restricting operations to this limited set of behaviors and data types.\n\nAn algebraic specification achieves these goals by defining one or more data types, and specifying a collection of functions that operate on those data types.  These functions can be divided into two classes:\n\n# [[Constructor (object-oriented programming)|constructor functions]]: functions that create or initialize the data elements, or construct complex elements from simpler ones\n# [[Method (computer programming)|additional functions]]: functions that operate on the data types, and are defined in terms of the constructor functions.\n\n==Example==\nConsider a formal algebraic specification for the [[Boolean data type|boolean]] data type.\n\nOne possible algebraic specification may provide two constructor functions for the data-element: a ''true'' constructor and a ''false'' constructor.  Thus, a boolean data element could be declared, constructed, and initialized to a value.  In this scenario, all other [[Boolean algebra|connective elements]], such as [[XOR]] and [[Logical conjunction|AND]], would be ''additional functions''.  Thus, a data element could be instantiated with either \"true\" or \"false\" value, and additional functions could be used to perform any operation on the data element.\n\nAlternatively, the entire system of boolean data types could be specified using a different set of constructor functions: a ''false'' constructor and a ''[[Negation|not]]'' constructor.  In that case, an additional function could be defined to yield the value \"true.\"\n\nThe algebraic specification therefore describes [[state machine|all possible states]] of the data element, and all possible [[State_machine#Concepts_and_vocabulary|transitions]] between states.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Common Algebraic Specification Language]]\n* [[Formal specification]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Formal methods]]\n\n\n{{compsci-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Algebraic specification''',<ref>{{cite book|title=Algebraic Specification|first=H.|last= Ehrig|author2=B. Mahr|publisher=Academic Press|year=1989|isbn=0-201-41635-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Algebraic Specification|first=J.A.|last=Bergstra|author2=J. Heering |author3=J. Klint |publisher=Springer-Verlag|year=1985|series=EATCS Monographs on Theoretical Computer Science|volume=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Algebraic Specification|first=M.|last=[[Martin Wirsing|Wirsing]]|series=Handbook of Theoretical Computer Science|volume=B|editor=[[Jan van Leeuwen]]|year=1990|publisher=Elsevier|pages=675\u2013788}}</ref> is a software engineering technique for [[formal specification|formally specifying]] system behavior.  Algebraic specification seeks to systematically develop more efficient programs by:\n\n# formally defining [[data type|types of data]], and mathematical operations on those data types\n# abstracting implementation details, such as the size of representations (in memory) and the efficiency of obtaining outcome of computations\n# formalizing the computations and operations on data types\n# allowing for automation by formally restricting operations to this limited set of behaviors and data types.\n\nAn algebraic specification achieves these goals by defining one or more data types, and specifying a collection of functions that operate on those data types.  These functions can be divided into two classes:\n\n# [[Constructor (object-oriented programming)|constructor functions]]: functions that create or initialize the data elements, or construct complex elements from simpler ones\n# [[Method (computer programming)|additional functions]]: functions that operate on the data types, and are defined in terms of the constructor functions.\n\n==Example==\nConsider a formal algebraic specification for the [[Boolean data type|boolean]] data type.\n\nOne possible algebraic specification may provide two constructor functions for the data-element: a ''true'' constructor and a ''false'' constructor.  Thus, a boolean data element could be declared, constructed, and initialized to a value.  In this scenario, all other [[Boolean algebra|connective elements]], such as [[XOR]] and [[Logical conjunction|AND]], would be ''additional functions''.  Thus, a data element could be instantiated with either \"true\" or \"false\" value, and additional functions could be used to perform any operation on the data element.\n\nAlternatively, the entire system of boolean data types could be specified using a different set of constructor functions: a ''false'' constructor and a ''[[Negation|not]]'' constructor.  In that case, an additional function could be defined to yield the value \"true.\"\n\nThe algebraic specification therefore describes [[state machine|all possible states]] of the data element, and all possible [[State_machine#Concepts_and_vocabulary|transitions]] between states.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Common Algebraic Specification Language]]\n* [[Donald Sannella]]\n* [[Formal specification]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Formal methods]]\n\n\n{{compsci-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dsannella", "label": "safe", "comment": "Replaced my name under \"See also\", which seems misplaced, with a reference to my book with Andrzej Tarlecki on the topic of this article.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_specification"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States presidential election in Florida", "text_new": "{{main|2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2020 [[United States presidential election]] in Florida\n| country = Florida\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2016 United States presidential election in Florida\n| previous_year     = 2016\n| election_date = November 3, 2020\n| next_election     = 2024 United States presidential election in Florida\n| next_year         = 2024\n| turnout = %\n| image_size = \n\n| image1 = Donald Trump official portrait (cropped).jpg\n| nominee1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Florida]]\n| running_mate1 = [[Mike Pence]]\n| electoral_vote1 =\n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n\n| image2 = Joe Biden 2013.jpg\n| nominee2 = [[Joe Biden]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Delaware]]\n| running_mate2 = TBA\n| electoral_vote2 =\n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Donald Trump]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = TBA\n| after_party = \n}}\n{{ElectionsFL}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States presidential election in Florida''' is scheduled to take place on Tuesday, November 3, 2020, as part of the [[2020 United States elections]] in which all 50 states plus the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] will participate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-elections-key-dates-midterms-2020-presidential-house-congress-senate-a8472821.html|title=US elections key dates: When are the 2018 midterms and the 2020 presidential campaign?|last=Kelly|first=Ben|date=August 13, 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Florida]] voters will choose electors to represent them in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] via a popular vote. The state of Florida has 29 electoral votes in the Electoral College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/allocation.html|title=Distribution of Electoral Votes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Miami Beach, Florida]], which hosted the [[1972 Democratic National Convention]], was a finalist to host the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/miami-beach/article213670709.html|title=Cruise ship hotels, zoo parties and an NBA arena: Miami's Democratic convention pitch|work=miamiherald|access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref> The other finalists were Milwaukee and Houston. Milwaukee was ultimately decided as the host.<ref name=\":0FL\">{{Cite news|url=https://fox6now.com/2018/06/20/city-of-milwaukee-named-as-1-of-3-finalists-to-host-2020-dnc-convention/|title=City of Milwaukee 1 of 3 finalists to host 2020 Democratic National Convention|date=2018-06-20|work=FOX6Now.com|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/08/22/dnc-team-visiting-milwaukee-2020-democratic-convention-site/1065267002/|title=Selection committee for 2020 Democratic Convention will visit Milwaukee next week|last=Glauber|first=Bill|date=August 22, 2018|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFlorida will also be incumbent president Donald Trump's home state for this election, after having identified New York as his home in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/31/us/politics/trump-new-york-florida-primary-residence.html|title=Trump, Lifelong New Yorker, Declares Himself a Resident of Florida|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|date=November 4, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> As a result, Trump became the first nominee of either major party to be from Florida.\n\n==Primary elections==\nThe primary elections were held on March 17, 2020.\n\n===Republican primary===\nThe Florida secretary of state declared [[Rocky de la Fuente]] to be a major candidate and thus worthy of automatic inclusion on the ballot.\n \n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Republican primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\nThree Democrats were still in race by the time Florida held its primaries: [[Vermont]] [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Bernie Sanders]], former [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] [[Joe Biden]], and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] from [[Hawaii]] [[Tulsi Gabbard]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=Elizabeth Warren Formally Announces 2020 Presidential Bid in Lawrence, Mass. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-2020.html |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=The New York Times |date=9 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Li |title=Kamala Harris announces her historic 2020 presidential campaign |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/1/21/18175628/kamala-harris-2020-campaign-president |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=Vox |date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Detrow |first1=Scott |title=Cory Booker Makes It Official: He's Running For President In 2020 |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/01/676578945/cory-booker-makes-it-official-hes-running-for-president-in-2020 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=NPR |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first Democratic debate took place in [[Miami]] over two nights at the end of June 2019. It was broadcast on several of the [[NBC]] networks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/first-democratic-debate-2020-election|title=First Democratic Debate 2019: Highlights, candidates and more|website=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Democratic primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/sites/default/files/2020-03/EC%20030920.4.pdf|title=2020 POTUS Race ratings|website=The Cook Political Report|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside Elections]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideelections.com/ratings/president|title=POTUS Ratings {{!}} Inside Elections|website=insideelections.com|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|April 3, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-president/|title=Larry J. Sabato's Crystal Ball \u00bb 2020 President|website=crystalball.centerforpolitics.org|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Lean|R}}\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Politico]]<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.politico.com/2020-election/race-forecasts-and-predictions/president/ |title=2020 Election Forecast|date=November 19, 2019 |publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|November 19, 2019\n|}\n\n===Polling===\n====Aggregate polls====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!colspan=\"7\"|Donald Trump vs. Joe Biden\n|-\n!Source of poll aggregation\n!Dates administered\n!Dates updated\n![[Joe Biden]]\n![[Donald Trump]]\n!Other/Undecided{{Efn|Calculated by taking the difference of 100% and all other candidates combined.|name=|group=}}\n!Margin\n|-\n|[https://www.270towin.com/2020-polls-biden-trump/florida/ 270 to Win]\n|March 16, 2020 - April 6, 2020\n|April 6, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''45.5%'''\n|44.0%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|{{hs|1.5}}'''Biden + 1.5'''\n|-\n|[https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/fl/florida_trump_vs_biden-6841.html Real Clear Politics]\n|March 5, 2020 - April 4, 2020\n|April 4, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''46.7%'''\n|46.3%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}